http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-4543.html&cid=1116924013&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Bush asks for $30bn to fight AIDS worldwide- from Pink News- all the latest gay news from the gay community - Pink News Receive our daily newsletter Bush asks for $30bn to fight AIDS worldwide Current US law dictates that one-third of prevention funding through PEPFAR must teach exclusively abstinence-only until marriage. Click here to read and make Comments on this article Receive our daily news update Bishop: Church must overcome homophobia Students protest gay donor ban Students encouraged to give blood because gays and bisexuals can't Chlamydia epidemic targets US gays Recent comments across PinkNews.co.uk 2nd June 2007 22:00 President Bush has called on the United States Congress to double U.S. funding towards fighting the global AIDS pandemic. He requested $30 billion through the President's Emergency Programme for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) for the first five years after he leaves office. The President first announced his plans to create PEPFAR, a five year, $15 billion dollar initiative to combat AIDS worldwide, during his 2003 State of the Union Address. PEPFAR funding supports various HIV/AIDS programmes, which provide access to antiretroviral drugs, treatment, and prevention in fifteen focus countries, in addition to many other countries hard hit by the AIDS pandemic. The programme is currently set to expire on September 30, 2008. "Twenty-six years after the first reported AIDS case in the U.S., HIV and AIDS continues to devastate communities both at home and abroad, and our nation's leadership must harness all possible resources to confront the epidemic," said gay lobby group Human Rights Campaign President Joe Solmonese. "Though the PEPFAR programme has provided life-saving treatment for millions of people with HIV/AIDS worldwide, we continue to have grave concerns over the misguided restrictions on prevention funding. "Our nation's experts agree that the abstinence earmark only exacerbates the challenges in providing effective and culturally appropriate prevention messages to stem the transmission of the epidemic. "We urge Congress to lift these restrictions based purely on ideology and instead fund proven science-based prevention strategies." Current US law dictates that one-third of prevention funding through PEPFAR must teach exclusively abstinence-only until marriage. A 2006 report from the General Accountability Office (GAO) found that seventeen of the twenty countries surveyed reported that the abstinence earmark "challenges their ability to develop interventions that are responsive to local epidemiology and social norms." Furthermore, the GAO reported that in order to comply with the abstinence earmark, many countries were forced to significantly cut funding for prevention efforts to reach those most at risk, including programmes designed to prevent mother-to-child transmission of the HIV virus. In 2007, the Institute of Medicine (IOM) likewise criticised the abstinence earmark as well as the programme's ban on funding needle exchange programs as obstacles to the programme's effectiveness. Representatives Barbara Lee (Democrat, California) and Christopher Shays (Republican, Connecticut) have introduced the Protection Against Transmission of HIV for Women and Youth Act of 2007 which would eliminate the abstinence-only earmark in PEPFAR. © 2007. GayWired.com; All Rights Reserved. Berlin memorial to persecuted gays Christian groups fight gay equality laws Angels in America AIDS gala Californian gay prisoners get conjugal visits On the blog now Jim Carrey gay romance film Any Dream Will Do- goodbye Ben Ellis Beth Ditto: Blame gay men for skinny ladies More from the blog Associate Programme Coordinator, Stonewall Fundraising Officer, National Aids Trust JGames.co.uk play free java and flash games at work
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-0&fd=R&url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003733632_murray04m.html&cid=1116954432&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Local News | Gates grant for health institute is UW's largest | Seattle Times Newspaper Send us news tips Monday, June 4, 2007 - Page updated at 09:02 AM Gates grant for health institute is UW's largest Seattle Times education reporter Leading health researcher Chris Murray heads the health-metrics institute funded by Bill Gates' foundation. Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation today announced a $105 million grant to launch an institute at the University of Washington that experts say will strengthen Seattle's growing reputation in global health research. The grant to create the Institute of Health Metrics and Evaluation is the single largest gift to the UW. The university is contributing an additional $20 million. Combined, the money is earmarked to launch and operate the institute for 10 years. The institute will be run by Chris Murray, a Harvard professor and global health leader who's been recruited for the job. The institute will evaluate international health programs and spending. UW President Mark Emmert said Monday the institute's work will get underway soon in existing UW facilities, but that there are no immediate plans for a new building. The new institute has a web site: The institute will be guided by an international board of health experts chaired by Dr. Julio Frenk, Mexico's former minister of health and a senior fellow at the Gates Foundation. Murray seemed almost destined to tackle world health problems: As a boy, when others his age were learning to ride bikes and fish, he was traveling across Africa with his parents as they set up health clinics and ran hospitals. "It was pretty captivating," Murray, 44, said in a recent interview. "I never really thought much about careers, but I always knew I'd do something in global health." He would later win a Rhodes scholarship, graduate magna cum laude from Harvard University with a medical degree and become a top official at the World Health Organization. News of the institute, due to open in the fall, first surfaced in February when UW regents discussed draft plans for the project. The university is expected to put in some money for the institute, but most will come from the Gates Foundation. The institute was to have been at Harvard, but software mogul Larry Ellison last year rescinded a promised gift of $115 million, citing leadership concerns after the departure of former Harvard President Lawrence Summers. Murray said he plans to bring several junior researchers with him from Harvard and other universities, and he hopes to recruit other talent from around the world. The institute will focus on research and will not offer undergraduate degrees, he said, although it will offer a master's degree program for 25 to 40 students. Murray officially became a UW employee May 1 and will be paid $420,000 in his first year, making him one of the UW's &#8212; and the state's &#8212; highest-paid employees. He grew up in the rural New Zealand town of Matamata, later immortalized as the setting for Hobbiton in "The Lord of the Rings" movie trilogy. He went to high school in Minnesota after his parents, a doctor and a microbiologist, moved there to work at the Mayo Clinic. His work defies simple explanation. One way to think about it, he said, is to compare the health-care world to the business world. In business, everyone knows exactly how much money is invested in a company, how much its products sell for and how much profit results, Murray said. "We can't imagine doing business without it. But when you turn to health care, we don't have it," Murray said. "When people in business cheat and break the rules, like with Enron, there's an extraordinary scandal. Yet we don't know what we get for all these large investments in health care." That lack of accountability prompted Murray and colleague Alan Lopez in the early 1990s to develop a measure for the global "burden of disease" &#8212; a systematic, numeric way to quantify health problems in terms of deaths, life years lost and years compromised by illness. Lopez, who now heads the public-health school at the University of Queensland in Australia, recalls how Murray and he developed much of the model while working out of an unheated barn in Maine. "For a period of 12 months, it was absolute hell," Lopez said. "We were doing something that had never been done before: measuring the health of the world. He had no doubt we could do it, while I had every doubt we could ever do it." The pair came up with 50,000 separate measures of health, Lopez said. But their work wasn't warmly received. One key measure they developed &#8212; called Disability Affected Life Years, or DALY &#8212; was derided by public-health leaders at the time, who accused the pair of making unethical judgments and comparisons about disease and suffering. "We called them the DALY wars. The public-health community railed against Chris in particular," Lopez said. "It was a very tumultuous period of four to six years." But Lopez said one person who took a shine to the work was Bill Gates, who began carrying the pair's summary book with him everywhere. Whenever someone would ask him for money, according to Lopez, Gates would quiz them about their "burden of disease" measurement. Eventually, the wider public-health community &#8212; and the World Health Organization &#8212; also came to embrace the measure, now seen as an important yardstick in health-care accountability. Murray said his research turned up some surprising results about problems in the developing world. While people had previously focused on illnesses such as malaria, AIDS and tuberculosis, Murray said they found three problems were being largely ignored: mental health, traffic injuries and heart disease/diabetes. Those findings helped shift people's perceptions &#8212; and their resources. "It had a reasonably significant effect on what's on the policy agenda," Murray said. Colleagues of Murray describe him as hard-working, focused and possessing an uncanny ability to unearth meaning from obscure data. In an e-mail, Harvard School of Public Health Dean Barry Bloom said Murray is "one of those rare academics who've really changed the world." "He's a phenomenon," Lopez said. "He's an extraordinary intellect and a driver in global health." Copyright &#169; 2007 The Seattle Times Company More local news headlines... Hiking accident, hit-and-run claim Inglemoor grads You may become medical guinea pig without knowing it Credit scorer aims to end "rental" of good ratings Motorcycle ridership grows; rider death rate grows faster Despite a warm day, M's Feierabend keeps cool for 1st win Obama and Edwards clash sharply on war in 2nd debate Light-rail debt a 50-year ride Gates grant for health institute is UW's largest Paris Hilton checks into L.A. jail for three-week stay Trucks losing tires leave State Patrol at a loss Lisa Francoise's quirky Ravenna store deals in spa and beauty products made with chocolate, including lip balm and body wash. The Seattle Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-6&fd=R&url=http://www.registerguard.com/news/2007/06/04/ed.col.wyden.0604.p1.php%3Fsection%3Dopinion&cid=1116779746&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg The Register-Guard, Eugene, Oregon, USA 14-day Free Trial Offer Apply for a Route Place A Classified Ad View Real Estate Ads Jobs at the Register-Guard Apply for a Route Car & Truck Ads &bull; Duck men's basketball &bull; Duck women's basketball U of O Facilities Services Utilization Nurse Case Coord. VP of Finance (non-profit) RX FOR HEALTH CARE Act would provide universal health coverage Published: Monday, June 4, 2007 magine guaranteed, high-quality health insurance for every American, coverage that can never be lost or taken away. Imagine a health care system focused on wellness and prevention. Imagine that insurance companies are required to cover everyone regardless of pre-existing conditions, and that you can't be dropped and your rates can't be raised if you get sick. Imagine your health insurance is as good as every member of Congress gets. Those are the bedrock principles underlying the Healthy Americans Act, the first bipartisan health care reform bill in more than a decade. The last time federal policymakers attempted comprehensive health care reform, in 1994, we saw what happened without a bipartisan coalition pushing for reform: Business groups said we can't afford it, and the effort quickly died. Today, many businesses are saying we can't afford to do health care reform. That change - combined with continual grass-roots efforts such as the ones we've seen in Oregon - has opened a window for real reform. The question is: Now that we have this window of opportunity, what should our health care system look like? Folks in Oregon, in particular, have put forward worthy proposals. The 100 Percent Access Coalition in Lane County, former Gov. John Kitzhaber's Archimedes Movement, the Oregon Business Council Health Care Task Force, and state Sens. Alan Bates and Ben Westlund all have done wonderful work. But there is no way the states can comprehensively fix health care because the states didn't create the problems. Who did? The federal government did, as the biggest spender of health care dollars in America and the architect of the policies now driving health care toward implosion. So how do we tackle this issue at the national level? The Healthy Americans Act is a road map to providing universal health coverage for the same cost we, as a nation, currently are paying. It works like this: Employers who provide employee health benefits would have to convert their workers' health care premiums into higher wages for two years. Employers who do not offer health benefits would be required to make phased-in "employer shared responsibility payments," which would be used to provide financial assistance to individuals and families with modest incomes. After two years, every employer would make these payments, the size of which would be determined by their ability to pay. In turn, every American would have to purchase private health coverage. To make sure that it's affordable, the plan would pay the full premiums for those who live below the federal poverty line, while folks between 100 percent and 400 percent of the federal poverty line would receive subsidies on a sliding scale. The insurance industry also will have to reform. By law, insurers would no longer be allowed to cherry-pick their customers. Currently, insurance companies can choose which customers they sign up - typically the healthy ones - and send those in fragile health to even more fragile government programs. Instead, insurance companies would be required to insure everyone who signs up, no matter their pre-existing conditions, age or gender. And they would be prohibited from raising prices if individuals are sick or are at risk of becoming sick. Prohibiting cherry picking would mean insurance companies finally would be competing with one another on the basis of price, service and health care outcomes, meaning consumers would be the real winners. This prohibition also would give insurance companies a financial incentive to invest in your health, which means we will see movement away from "sick care" and toward real health care, including wellness programs and preventive care. Some on the right want more tax breaks for the wealthy and no universal health care. Some on the left want all insurance companies put out of business. The political reality is that there isn't anywhere close to 60 votes - the number required to move any meaningful legislation under Senate rules - for either proposition. My responsibility is to find ways to bring Democrats and Republicans together to win universal health care as quickly as possible. But even with bipartisan support, making these changes won't be easy. The conventional wisdom is that we'll have to wait until after the presidential race is over before Congress again attempts comprehensive health care reform. I don't think the uninsured and the underinsured can afford to wait that long, so I'm asking Oregonians to help me keep pushing for change now. Let's seize this opportunity. Let's finally reform our broken health care system and provide high quality, affordable coverage for all Americans. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., is a member of the U.S. Senate Finance Committee, which has jurisdiction over health care laws. This essay is the eighth in a biweekly series of columns on health care reform. Subscribe to The Register-Guard >> Your browser does not support inline frames or is currently configured not to display inline frames. Content may be viewed at http://simg.zedo.com/intercept/tag/int401.html Copyright &copy; 2007 &mdash; The Register-Guard, Eugene, Oregon, USA
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-5&fd=R&url=http://www.spokesmanreview.com/breaking/story.asp%3FID%3D10154&cid=1116954432&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg SR.com: Gates Foundation launches global health institute Submit a news tip Home & Garden &raquo; 84&deg; F mostly sunny Gates Foundation launches global health institute SEATTLE (AP) – The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation is giving $105 million to the University of Washington to open a new research center to assess the performance of global health programs. The donation announced today is the largest private gift the university has ever received, university President Mark A. Emmert said. The university – which receives more government money for scientific research than any other public university – is also putting $20 million toward the new institute. "There has been a huge increase in resources for global health in recent years, and it's essential to evaluate the impact of these investments. With high-quality data, we can ensure resources go where they are needed most, and dramatically improve health care delivery," said Dr. Tadataka "Tachi" Yamada, president of the Gates Foundation's Global Health Program, in a statement issued before the official announcement. The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation will be directed by Christopher J.L. Murray, the former director of Harvard's institute for public health. Murray was chosen to lead the Ellison Institute for World Health at Harvard until last year, until Oracle Corp. founder Larry Ellison pulled the $115 million he had promised to Harvard. The University of Washington research center will collect and analyze data on health indicators and trends, such as the availability of health care and the spread of disease. It will study the results of health programs and will make health data freely available to policy-makers, researchers and the public. The university said it expects the institute to hire more than 100 faculty and staff and set up a collaboration network among research centers. "We hope to set the gold standard for scientifically rigorous evaluation in health," said Murray, a health economist. The institute will be led by a board of health experts chaired by Dr. Julio Frenk, a senior fellow at the Gates Foundation and Mexico's former minister of health. Enter your search terms River Park Square independent analysis Details and conversations on the Washington News Council's analysis of River Park Square coverage &raquo; a journal of their experiences &raquo; All Cougs, All the Time WSU schedule, stories, photos Latest news from AP Group Claims Captured Troops Were Killed Rep. Jefferson Indicted in Bribery Probe Bush Opens Europe Trip on Jarring Note Judge Dismisses Charges Against Detainee Group Denies Link to NYC Terror Plot Women Prosecuted for Smuggling Children Scientists Find 24 Species in Suriname Last updated at 1:39 p.m. The Spokesman-Review is in its 125th year of publishing. Take with photos, historic pages and more. Ocularist Kim Erickson creates custom artificial eyes for people who have lost an eye to disease or injury. Officer Lee Newbill Memorial The Legacy of the Olmsted Brothers Time on His Hands Colin's Video Journal &raquo; Subscribe to video in iTunes &raquo; More live shows &raquo; Star Wars postage stamps Readers report local prices of our six-month series of editorial board conversations with community leaders. Streaming video of our weekday 4:30 p.m. news meeting: Catch up on this year's big event: Read from the past, or watch from the race. Check out our Bloomsday 2007 special section &raquo; page for stories, schedules, rosters and more. See our Zags online column for news and highlights, and share your views on the new L, 60-57 vs. Indiana: of American coalition personnel are over 3,100. See the year's River Park Square crash News is a Conversation : Readers discuss our news coverage. Latest posts: River plan draws fire Frontline airs Jim West story again : Notes from our daily ne