 poultry vaccination program and strong political efforts were credited with bringing the disease under control. The H5N1 strain is difficult for people to catch, but experts fear it could mutate into a form that spreads easily among people. It has killed at least 187 people worldwide, according to the World Health Organization Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music player. Today's Page One in Europe Today's Page One in Asia Adverti