http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/society/health/sex%2Band%2Bsleep%2Bproblems%2Blink/543272&cid=1116865706&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Channel 4 - News - Sex and sleep problems link Skip to main content Channel 4 News > About Channel 4 News Sex and sleep problems link Last Modified: 03 Jun 2007 Pity the office lech who looks thoroughly burned out but still cannot keep his hands to himself. He may be suffering from "sexsomnia", according to the latest research from psychiatrists. The term describes a condition in which abnormal sexual behaviour is associated with sleep disorders. People who suffer severe, chronic insomnia may also exhibit a surge in sex drive, genital arousal, and "compulsive sexual behaviours", say researchers. Often the effects of "sexsomnia" emerge at night and coincide with sleep disturbances. Sleepwalking and "confusional arousal" - when a person performs unconscious complex actions while still asleep - may be accompanied by sexual vocalisations, fondling, sexual aggression and even sexual intercourse. In some cases, "sexsomnia" behaviour can be upsetting or frightening for the sleeper&#039;s partner. Dr Carlos Schenck, senior psychiatrist at the Minnesota Regional Sleep Disorders Centre in Minneapolis, who led a review of documented cases of the phenomenon, said: "It seems that more and more reports are surfacing of abnormal sexual behaviours emerging during sleep. "While people may think this type of behaviour is humorous, in reality it can be disturbing, annoying, embarrassing and a potentially serious problem for some individuals and couples. "Despite their awareness of the condition, many sufferers often delay seeking help, either because they don&#039;t know that it&#039;s a medical disorder, or for fear that others will instead judge it as wilful behaviour." Dr Schenck and fellow researchers conducted computerised literature searches of journal articles and scoured text books and other sources for information on sexual behaviours associated with sleep disorders. A list of "sexsomnia" sleep problems compiled by the team appears in the June issue of the journal Sleep. These news feeds are provided by an independent third party and Channel 4 is not responsible or liable to you for the same. Send this article to a friend Related Articles in Health Pubs urged &#039;display alcohol units&#039; Harman backs junk food ad watershed Abortion &#039;risk to mental health&#039; Mastectomies &#039;could be cut by drug&#039; &#039;Infighting&#039; fears in doctor row Water Cooler Moments &raquo; You saw it happen We tell you why The crucial issues from Week in pictures &raquo; The biggest stories and the best pictures. The Blair Quiz &raquo; So how much do you remember? Check your As, Bs and Cs here. Single, anxious female &raquo; Forget soccer moms. This is the demographic they&#039;re all talking about. Jump to main content
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-6&fd=R&url=http://www.dogflu.ca/06042007/10/test_your_fertility_at_home&cid=1116950771&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Test Your Fertility At Home | DogFlu.ca Ontario Animal Shelter Contact Information Health Information for Human Beings Human Conditions and Diseases Test Your Fertility At Home It is being reported that a new test has been developed to allow couples to check their level of fertility from the comfort of their own homes without needing to go to a doctor's office It is being reported that a new test has been developed to allow couples to check their level of fertility from the comfort of their own homes without needing to go to a doctor's office. The new at-home screening test is called Fertell, and comes with both his and her components. The test for the male, works by assessing the ability of a man's sperm to swim through a solution similar to cervical mucus, as well as the number able to do so, said Dr. Keith B. Isaacson, an assistant professor of obstetrics, gynecology and reproductive biology at Harvard Medical School. The female test, is a urine stick that measures the level of follicle-stimulating hormone on the third day of the menstrual cycle. An abnormally high level, is an indicator that the woman's egg quality is low. Genosis is the name of the company that makes the Fertell test and some doctors state that although it is a neat device, it may not catch any specific problems relating to a man or woman's fertility level: "The FSH test that we do in our officeâ€” that's actually in this kitâ€” is the first test we look for when a woman comes for an evaluation," said Dr. Harry Fisch of the Columbia University Medical Center. "This test is not a guarantee that you're fertile or not," Fisch said. "But it's a great start." Click Here to Join the Discussion! at 2007-06-04 14:04 | Copyright Â© 2006 DogFlu.Ca All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-0&fd=R&url=http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/beauty/article1849690.ece&cid=1116867696&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Sunscreen is the snake oil of the 21st-century,&rdquo; said Samuel Rudman, a lawyer at Lerach Coughlin, announcing that the firm was filing a class-action lawsuit in the Los Angeles Superior Court against five leading sunscreen manufacturers. Rudman&rsquo;s allegation &ndash; that the companies behind household names such as Hawaiian Tropic and Neutrogena were misleading consumers about the cancer-protective powers of their products &ndash; was based on the evidence of consumers who had worn sunscreen, but still contracted skin cancer." /> Still in the shade-Life & Style-Women-Beauty-TimesOnline Best of the weekend, from The Times and The Sunday Times Navigation - link to other main sections from here No wonder I'll die alone. All I do is ask questions Still in the shade Just because suncream has a high SPF number doesn&#8217;t mean it will protect you from harmful UVA rays that can lead to wrinkles and cancer, says Anjana Gosaia to not show photographer information --> to not show image description --> to not show enlarge option --> Sunscreen is the snake oil of the 21st-century,&rdquo; said Samuel Rudman, a lawyer at Lerach Coughlin, announcing that the firm was filing a class-action lawsuit in the Los Angeles Superior Court against five leading sunscreen manufacturers. Rudman&rsquo;s allegation &ndash; that the companies behind household names such as Hawaiian Tropic and Neutrogena were misleading consumers about the cancer-protective powers of their products &ndash; was based on the evidence of consumers who had worn sunscreen, but still contracted skin cancer. It sent tremors across the sun-kissed beaches of the Californian coastline. The outcome of this case is still pending, but it&rsquo;s not just our sun-spoilt friends on Santa Monica beach who should be sweating. With Britons set to bask in another scorching summer, even the more sun-savvy tanners, who slather on a high SPF, may not be as protected as they think. Why? Because the SPF rating on the average sunscreen relates only to UVB rays that cause sunburn and are associated with the development of skin cancer, not the wrinkle-causing UVA rays, which, until recently, were thought to be relatively harmless. However, it is now believed that UVA rays penetrate the skin, distorting the structure of cells, elastin and collagen. The cumulative damage is irreversible and can go undetected for years. A growing number of scientists think that prolonged exposure to UVA rays greatly contributes to melanoma, the deadliest skin cancer. Brian Diffey, professor of photobiology at Newcastle University, warns: &ldquo;By 2035, there could be 21,000 new cases of melanoma a year in the UK, as those who sunburnt badly in the 1980s and 1990s suffer the long-term effects.&rdquo; Yet millions of people are oblivious to this time bomb and will still spend hours in the sun, striving for a perfect bronze glow. Dr Des Fernandes, a plastic surgeon and founder of Environ skincare, claims that 60% of UVA rays penetrate even the best sunblock. If this is the case, why are we no clearer on what UVA protection sunscreens offer? The problem is that the men in white coats and beauty corporations have failed to establish a universal, SPF-type rating system for UVA, because they have yet to agree on a method of measuring the effectiveness of UVA-blocking products. So, while protection against UVB rays is indicated with a number, such as SPF 15, UVA protection is denoted in many different ways, including broad-spectrum, broad-band protection, numbers and stars. Boots has been commended for attempting to bring clarity to the issue by introducing the star-rating system for UVA protection as early as 1991. However, Cancer Research UK describes it as &ldquo;vague&rdquo; and &ldquo;confusing&rdquo; in the way it measures UVA protection only in relation to UVB: for example, a high-SPF sunscreen with two stars may give better overall protection than a low SPF with three stars. And other critics point out that the star system does not account for photostability (the ability of the product to remain on the skin during sun exposure). Faced with the challenge of creating a standardised guide to UVA protection, beauty companies argue that as long as there is no universal method to objectively measure the long-term effects of UVA on the skin, such a system seems a long way off. Animal testing has proved inconclusive: tests on mice suggest that UVB rays cause melanoma; tests on fish found UVA rays incubated the disease. As Chris Flower of the Cosmetic, Toiletry and Perfumery Association (CTPA), a group that promotes the interests of companies such as Estée Lauder, Johnson & Johnson and Procter & Gamble, says: &ldquo;It takes time to prove a scientific theory. If UVA takes years to lead to premature ageing, how are you going to test the product&rsquo;s benefit if it won&rsquo;t show for years?&rdquo; Various companies claim to have discovered their own &ldquo;ground-breaking&rdquo; products to protect against UVA rays. L&rsquo;Oréal says its patented filters, Mexoryl SX and Mexoryl XL, contained in brands such as Ambre Solaire, form the most effective UVA filtering system available. Other companies suggest that mineral filters &ndash; the zinc oxide and titanium dioxide contained in Z01 Body Protection Lotion, for example &ndash; provide the best broad-band UVA and UVB protection. Fernandes believes his Environ range of antioxidant-rich products will fight the free radicals caused by sun exposure, and that this is crucial to preventing skin cancer. The New York dermatologist Dr Dennis Gross, the man behind MD Skincare, says the answer lies in chelators, a group of metal-binding molecules. He believes chelator-rich products counteract iron, an aggressive free radical found on the skin that generates other free radicals, which, in turn, are a trigger for skin cancer. However, many scientists say that nobody can lay claim to the ultimate UVA protection. &ldquo;Skincare companies are not the founts of all knowledge. Their primary objective is to sell products,&rdquo; says Diffey. &ldquo;There are active ingredients that can provide equal, if not broader, UVA screening than Mexoryl. The protection provided by antioxidants is small; as for chelators, reducing free-radical damage can help, but shade and clothing can provide you with 10 times the protection of these ingredients.&rdquo; His only advice to people wanting to protect themselves from harmful rays is: &ldquo;Stay indoors with the curtains closed.&rdquo; But, as we head into the holiday season, that is not going to happen. However, there is hope on the horizon. The European Cosmetic Toiletry and Perfumery Association (Colipa) has developed a test-tube (in vitro) method of assessing UVA protection that meets European commission recommendations. This could form the basis for a universal system, but initially it would apply only to Europe. The CTPA has indicated that it plans to adopt Colipa&rsquo;s standardised system, but due to product cycles, sunscreens featuring the Colipa logo will not appear until next year. Seemingly, sun-worshippers will have to remain in the shade for at least one more summer. CREAMS WITH UVA PROTECTION Environ RAD Antioxidant Sunscreen, &pound;15.95; 020 8450 2020 Garnier Ambre Solaire Moisturising Protection Milk SPF20, &pound;10.49 MD Skincare All-in-one Tinted Moisturizer Sunscreen SPF15, &pound;32, from Space NK; 020 8740 2085 ZO1 Body Protection Lotion, &pound;14.50; 01753 759746 An effective UVA sunblock would stain the skin and clothes yellow. Turmeric would be effective and safe. Thus UVA sunscreen is a marketing issue, not a technical issue. Keith Beatty, San Diego, CA * Town / City Save to my times Women sue over wrinkle cure they say didn&rsquo;t work Beauty style: The Sybari