art of that re-evaluation, she retired from working in the Douglas County Childhood Development Association office and began serving as an inspiration to others through support groups such as Bosom Buddies and by volunteering. For nearly three years, she has been a volunteer in the Oncology Center, where she works from noon to 4 p.m. Wednesdays. While there, her jobs include serving and transporting patients, cleaning rooms and running errands. Stephanie Norris, a registered nurse at the center, said while Nelson provides those valuable services, she also can relate to what the patients are going through. â€œI think she knows what it is like to be sitting in that treatment chair,â€ Norris said. Wellsville native Ardena Yakle, who was receiving a treatment Wednesday, agreed. â€œI think itâ€™s nice to have a volunteer here who has been through chemo and the radiation and everything else,â€ said Yakle, who had a mastectomy in March and will be undergoing treatments until August. â€œWhen you see people who have survived it, you think you can, too.â€ Yakle plans to follow in Nelsonâ€™s footsteps and participate in her first Relay for Life on Friday. And Reaumur Donnally, also an Oncology Center volunteer, plans to cheer them on. He said the event can be motivational for anyone. â€œThe first lap is inspiring. You see the courage and optimism of cancer survivors of all ages,â€ he said. â€œItâ€™s a culture for healing, helping and moving forward.â€ Thatâ€™s exactly what Nelson has done. She now serves on the Relay for Life committee and is committed to raising awareness about cancer. The American Cancer Society estimates about 2.5 million new cancer cases will be diagnosed this year. â€œItâ€™s just amazing how much cancer touches lives these days,â€ Nelson said. She never expected to become a victim because it wasnâ€™t something that had been in her family. Now she urges her grown children â€” Donna Binns and Chris Nelson â€” to take extra precautions. Living through the or