http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-5&fd=R&url=http://blog.nola.com/times-picayune/2007/06/army_corps_trying_to_repair_it.html&cid=1116866873&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Army Corps trying to repair its image along with levees - Times-Picayune: Updates Murder-suicide suspected in Harvey 50 shots fired, 2 hurt, outside Fat City nightclub New Orleans police probing two shooting deaths State details $700M in rescue money for Road Home Motorcyclist killed after striking guardrail Today's Front Page news Army Corps trying to repair its image along with levees Cindy Chang, St. Tammany bureau June 02, 2007 10:52PM At a recent meeting, New Orleans Sewerage & Water Board member Penelope Randolph wondered whether the hydraulic pumps Col. Jeffrey Bedey had just touted could handle an upwelling of mud from Lake Pontchartrain if another Katrina strikes. "They can't pump sludge," she said, referring to the 17th Street Canal pumps. Bedey, who commands the Army Corps of Engineers' Hurricane Protection Office, had a ready answer: "The intent in an impending storm is to close the gates early, which prevents water and/or sludge from entering the canal." His audience may not have left the meeting entirely reassured, but then Bedey was defending a system of temporary pumps and gates that, while presumably stronger than what was in place pre-Katrina, still is only a stopgap measure in the quest for protection against a once-in-100-years hurricane. Each time he spars with the knowledgeable, skeptical public officials who have been betrayed by the corps once before, Bedey delivers more or less the same message: Much progress has been made in shoring up the area's levees and canals, but much work remains. Then come the tough questions, made more urgent by the start of a hurricane season that forecasters predict will be more severe than normal. But after the public grilling is over, most of his inquisitors give Bedey a thumbs-up review. A year after he arrived in New Orleans, the 47-year-old Bedey and his colleagues at the corps have accomplished a seemingly impossible public relations feat: They have won the grudging trust of city and parish officials whose constituents lost countless homes to the catastrophic breaches of corps levees after Hurricane Katrina. As commander of the Hurricane Protection Office, Bedey is in charge of flood protection on the east bank, including some of the area's most disaster-prone waterways: the 17th Street Canal, the Industrial Canal and the Mississippi River-Gulf Outlet. A lean 6-feet-5 in Army fatigues and brown lace-up boots, Bedey would be an intimidating physical presence but for his casual demeanor. He is as likely to put an arm around a disgruntled parish official as to defend himself with statistics. His unerring people skills have even transformed a few public meetings into veritable love fests, with local officials praising him for his honesty and accessibility. "The colonel is a very frank individual. He doesn't beat around the bush," said Chris Roberts, a Jefferson Parish councilman who has been openly critical of the corps. "That doesn't mean I'm satisfied with the corps' progress. The difference with Bedey is that if a deadline is not going to be reached, he's going to come to you as soon as he knows that. He's not one to say, 'We'll get it done, we'll get it done' and in the ninth inning change that." The positive vibes are conditioned, of course, on whether the corps can follow through on its promises not to fail the New Orleans region again. The good feelings will quickly sour, observers say, if it ever becomes clear that the talk is not being followed by action. While they grumble about the slow pace of work on specific projects, local officials are unstinting in their praise for Bedey and the corps' post-storm outreach initiative. For the first time, they say, the corps is treating them as partners rather than adversaries, showing up regularly to council meetings to solicit input and demonstrating a new willingness to share current information. "We need someone, whether it's good news or bad news, to tell us the truth, and Bedey's the man," said Jefferson Parish Council Chairman Tom Capella. "If it's bad news, we can figure out what the best step is. We don't want someone to withhold information or sugarcoat information. We can take the bad news, but we can't take misinformation." Bedey occupies one corner of a triangular command system established to deal with the enormous job of rebuilding and improving the New Orleans area's devastated levees and canals. Just days after the storm, the corps created Task Force Hope, eventually splitting the responsibilities into two parts: Bedey's Hurricane Protection Office and the Protection Restoration Office, headed by Col. Richard Wagenaar. The Protection Restoration Office's jurisdiction includes hurricane protection duties on the West Bank and in Jefferson and St. Charles parishes, in addition to the non-hurricane-related engineering jobs previously undertaken by the New Orleans district office. Karen Durham-Aguilera, a civilian engineer, succeeded Dan Hitchings as director of Task Force Hope and is the boss of the two colonels, who are equal-ranking in the organization. Collectively, they manage the $7 billion appropriated so far by Congress for New Orleans area hurricane protection. Durham-Aguilera, who came to the job five months ago after directing the corps' Northwestern Division, insisted on living in New Orleans rather than in Mississippi, where Hitchings had been based, because she wanted to be part of the city that she was serving. "To be really committed, to oversee this work that's so immense, that's such a huge mission, to establish relationships with the community -- you can't really do that right unless you're living here," Durham-Aguilera said. "For us, it's the only place to be. It's the place that was affected, it's the center of gravity for the work we're doing." A former champion bodybuilder, Durham-Aguilera views her position as one of her profession's few high-ranking women with a no-big-deal attitude, while recognizing that she is a role model for aspiring female leaders. When Katrina hit in August 2005, Durham-Aguilera was in Iraq, supervising government construction projects throughout the country. Bedey was in Nebraska, where he was commander and chief engineer of the Omaha District. Wagenaar, meanwhile, had arrived in New Orleans just a month before. He found himself in a bunker at the corps' Uptown headquarters commanding a skeleton crew of workers, some of whose names he had not yet had a chance to learn, as the levees gave way and the city flooded. On a helicopter flyover a few days later, he surveyed the extent of the damage. "I didn't know how it had gotten underwater, but my mind was processing the magnitude of the disaster. I couldn't believe it. It sucked the air out of me," Wagenaar said. That extraordinarily wrenching start, plus the marathon grind to repair the levees and then bring them to a 100-year protection level by 2011 in the face of an entrenched bureaucracy, has left Wagenaar "worn out," he said. Last November, he announced his retirement from the corps. He will be replaced in July by Col. Alvin Lee, who currently works at the construction equipment firm Caterpillar Inc. in Peoria, Ill., as a fellow in the Secretary of Defense Corporate Fellows Program. "I am tired, and it's just been so grueling, a two-year fight," Wagenaar said. "A lot of my immediate energy was spent fighting the normal bureaucratic rules, which are great in peacetime, terrible in an emergency." Much of the public relations duty has fallen to the two colonels, who directly oversee the manmade waterways that cut through the metropolitan area and leave it acutely vulnerable to hurricane surges. Bedey, in charge of the most intensely scrutinized levee structures and blessed with a guy-next-door likeability, has, to some extent, stolen the show. While Wagenaar's weariness is visible, Bedey seems to stand slightly above the fray, sometimes wearing a bemused expression or indulging in jokey asides. He powers through the long days on a diet of coffee and cigarettes, rarely stopping for lunch, chauffeured from appointment to appointment in a white Chevy Trailblazer by a public relations official. Slogans, like "shaping today and securing tomorrow," come readily to him, and he repeats them with the conviction of a football coach, a skill perhaps learned during his days as a high school star in Hamilton, Mont., and then an offensive guard at Montana State University. Bedey was pulled prematurely from Omaha normally a three-year posting to fill the new position of HPO commander, which he assumed almost exactly a year ago. The unusual circumstances of his call-to-duty have given him a sense of mission above and beyond the normal motivation to prevent a disaster like Katrina from happening again. "It's certainly a challenge, but life is made of challenges. This is a very, very important mission. The No.Â¤1 domestic priority mission in the Corps of Engineers is the hurricane recovery effort. The only thing that overshadows it is the global war on terror," Bedey said. The public presentations are only a streamlined distillation of Bedey's technical work with fellow engineers about how to solve the flood protection problems for which even the billions of dollars allocated by Congress after Katrina may not be enough. His crew has spent much of its energy on temporary solutions until the specifics of the plan for protection against a once-in-a-100-year storm are ironed out. In the end, success on both the technical and PR fronts is vital to the corps, which, no matter what it accomplishes in the present, will always be dogged by the enormity of its past failures. "You can build stuff, but if you don't have strong relationships, you will not be seen as good as you should be," Bedey said. "On the other hand, if you're great at relationships but you can't get anything done, you're like the guy who, you'd like to get a beer with John, play golf with John, but you'd never let John touch your car, because he's the worst mechanic." Bedey's long commute on the Causeway from his home off Brewster Road near Madisonville is an opportunity to catch up on work-related phone business. Yet he manages to make it back across the lake twice a week in time for his 13-year-old son's baseball games. His two older children attend Mandeville High, and his wife, Amy, is studying for degrees in English and psychology. On weekends, Bedey mows his one-acre plot just like any other suburban dad. Like most Army officers, Bedey has lived all over the map. During a stint in Pakistan while studying for a second master's degree in defense and strategic studies (his first is in construction engineering), he learned to cook biryani and chicken tikka. Since then, the South Asian restaurants stateside have paled in comparison with the real thing. But Bedey has landed in the right place to engage in one of his favorite hobbies -- fishing. His younger son is catching on, too, hooking two large redfish at one of his father's work stomping grounds, the MR-GO. On a clear, windy Friday in late May, Bedey took officials from St. Bernard Parish on a boat tour of the MR-GO. Flanking the waterway were levees of high-quality Mississippi clay to replace the slipshod ones that were almost obliterated by the storm. The slopes, covered with rye or Bermuda grass to increase stability, rose 20 feet above the water -- a big improvement over pre-storm levels but still short of the ideal of 24 feet or higher. While the tour was an illustration of progress made, it was also permeated with regret for a disaster that might have been prevented. If the levees had been in their current condition when Katrina hit, they might have prevented the destruction of St. Bernard Parish, said Councilman Craig Taffaro. Speaking to the officials on the boat, Bedey alluded to the possible closure of the MR-GO, which St. Bernard residents have long advocated, and pointed out the continued vulnerabilities of the Industrial Canal, which he termed the flood protection system's Achilles' heel. In an earlier interview, Councilman Joey DiFatta said he is happy that the corps seems to be making progress since the hurricane but that the same level of infrastructure investment and public outreach should have been in place years ago. He views Bedey as representative of the new corps -- more aggressive in attacking problems and more conscious of local residents' needs. "Everyone is now looking extremely closely at everything they do, making sure everything they do is proper, which is good, and that's the way it should have been for years and years," DiFatta said. "Maybe now we're getting the level of participation in the corps that we should have been getting for the last 50 years." Cindy Chang can be reached at cchang@timespicayune.com or (985) 898-4816. I LOVE READING STORIES LIKE THIS BECAUSE YOU FIND OUT ABOUT INDIVIDUAL PERSONALITY OUTSIDE OF THE WORK THEY ARE DOING AND FIND OUT THAT THEY ARE HUMANS JUST LIKE THE PEOPLE WHO READ THESE ARTICLES. I BELIEVE THAT THE LEVEES ARE STRONGER THAN THEY WERE IN JULY 2005 AND THE CORPS IS MAKING GREAT STRIDES IN BRINGING THE LEVEES BACK TO PRE-KATRINA STRENGTH AND I DON'T MEAN PRE-KATRINA STRENGTH AS IN AUGUST 28, 2005 CONDITION I MEAN LONG BEFORE KATRINA WHEN THE LEVEES WERE AT THEIR STRONGEST BEFORE THEY STARTED WEAKENING. PEOPLE WILL NEVER TRUST THE CORPS JUST BECAUSE THE IMAGES DURING THAT IMMEDIATE AFTERMATH WILL ALWAYS BE STUCK IN THE BACK OF PEOPLES MINDS AND THEY WILL REMEMBER HOW THE CORPS FAILED PEOPLE LONG BEFORE THE LEVEES BROKE BUT HOW MANY TIMES BEFORE HE LEVEES BROKE DID PEOPLE READ DAILY NEWS ABOUT WORK ON LEVEES AND HOW MANY TIMES BEFORE THE LEVEES BROKE DID THE SUBJECT OF LEVEES BECOME HOT TOPICS DURING LEGISLATIVE SESSIONS AND THE TOPIC OF THOSE IN CONGRESS. THE CORPS HAS DONE ABOUT 4