http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-0&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601103%26sid%3Da5KTUaA8wc88%26refer%3Dnews&cid=1116962886&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg , Jun 04 17:16 , Jun 04 22:16 , Jun 05 06:16 Australia & New Zealand Genentech&#39;s `Armed&#39; Herceptin Shrinks Breast Tumors (Update2) June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Genentech Inc., the world&#39;s largest maker of cancer-fighting drugs, said a charged-up version of its Herceptin drug for breast cancer shrank tumors in patients who failed to respond to other therapies. Four of 10 patients had their tumors shrink during a study, with minimal side effects, when taking a version of Herceptin linked to chemical toxins, researchers said at the American Society of Clinical Oncology meeting in Chicago. The combination is in the first of three phases generally needed for U.S. marketing approval. Genentech said its so-called `armed&#39; antibody will advance into a second-stage trial. One analyst said the more-potent form could generate $1.5 billion on its own, if approved by U.S. regulators. The currently marketed product had $1.2 billion in sales in 2006. ``This is the most exciting thing to me that we are doing,&#39;&#39; said Pamela Klein, Genentech&#39;s vice president of clinical hematology and oncology, in an interview yesterday. In April, when Genentech first announced it was testing the combination, analyst Geoffrey Porges of Sanford Bernstein & Co. in New York said the charged-up version may increase peak annual sales to $1.6 billion. Genentech makes the combination with ImmunoGen Inc. of Cambridge, Massachusetts, a partner that provides linking technology for the drug. In April, when Genentech first announced it was testing the combination, analyst Geoffrey Porges of Sanford Bernstein & Co. in New York said the charged-up version may increase peak annual sales to $1.6 billion. ImmunoGen&#39;s shares rose 2 cents to $5.94 at 4:00 p.m. New York time in Nasdaq Stock Market composite trading. The shares of South San Francisco based Genentech fell $1.55, or 2 percent, to $77.95 at 4:01 p.m. in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. The study was designed to measure safety, and the drug was generally well-tolerated, Klein said. No serious heart damage was seen, the most worrisome potential side effect, Klein said. The patients in the study were difficult to treat, and Klein said she didn&#39;t expect to see such a tumor response. She cautioned that the company needs to do further studies in a larger patient population, and has ``much work to do.&#39;&#39; The treatment binds tumor-killing chemicals to Herceptin, causing fewer side effects by attacking cancer cells and mostly leaving normal tissue alone. The research, presented late yesterday, may give Genentech a way to sell its standard Herceptin for early forms of breast cancer, and then provide the more potent therapy after the disease progresses. The strategy may spur new treatment practices for a disease diagnosed in more than 178,000 U.S. women a year. Herceptin had $1.2 billion in sales in 2006, making it Genentech&#39;s third-biggest drug behind cancer therapies Rituxan and Avastin. The drug also adds revenue for Basel, Switzerland- based drugmaker Roche AG, Genentech&#39;s largest shareholder. The more potent version could also help Genentech fend off competition from GlaxoSmithKline Plc.&#39;s Tykerb, analysts said. The U.S. Food and Drug Administration approved the rival drug, which also targets HER-2 proteins, in March. About one-fourth of breast cancer patients have tumors that carry excess amounts of HER-2 protein, the protein that Herceptin, an antibody drug, is designed to target, Genentech says. The drug works by blocking HER-2 positive cancer cells from dividing and growing. The new technology offers a different approach to earlier efforts that attached radiation to antibodies such as Herceptin, instead of toxic chemicals. Those approaches struggled commercially because oncologists must collaborate with nuclear medicine specialists, doctors say. Included in the old approach is Biogen Idec Inc.&#39;s radiation-antibody combination Zevalin, which recorded $16.4 million in sales in its fourth year on the market. The company is now seeking to divest that drug, according to the Cambridge, Massachusetts-based company&#39;s annual report with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Past combinations have failed because the toxins either snapped off in the blood before reaching the tumors or hit healthy cells on the way, causing side effects. Seattle Genetics, another collaborator of Genentech, says it has developed new synthetic linkers designed to remain stable in the blood, yet let go of its toxic payload inside tumors. ImmunoGen has worked on the linking technology since it was founded in 1981. The company doesn&#39;t yet have a marketed drug, or one in the final stage of testing, according to its Web site. To contact the reporter on this story: Luke Timmerman in San Francisco at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 16:22 EDT Related Media on Demand Desmond-Hellman of Genentech Reviews Herceptin, Avastin Factory Orders in U.S. Increased 0.3 Percent in April, Less Than Estimated Loews, XTO Will Buy Dominion&#39;s Onshore Oil, Gas Business for $6.5 Billion Oil Rises Above $66 on Increased Fuel Demand, Threats to Nigerian Supply
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-5&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601100%26sid%3DaXiXNdsOrdwM%26refer%3Dgermany&cid=1116946098&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg , Jun 04 17:16 , Jun 04 22:16 , Jun 05 06:16 Australia & New Zealand Onyx, Bayer&#39;s Nexavar Extends Life in Cancer Patients (Update5) By Luke Timmerman and Eva von Schaper June 4 (Bloomberg) -- Onyx Pharmaceuticals Inc. and Bayer AG said a study found their Nexavar drug is the first to help people live longer with liver cancer, driving Onyx&#39;s shares up 8.6 percent. Those who took Nexavar in the trial lived a median time of 10.7 months compared with 7.9 months for patients on a placebo, according to research presented at the American Society of Clinical Oncology meeting in Chicago. The difference meant patients lived 44 percent longer, researchers said. Onyx, based in Emeryville, California, and its marketing partner, Leverkusen, Germany-based Bayer, say they plan to submit the results to U.S. and European regulators imminently, and hope to have approval in 2008. The medicine would be a new option against a disease that kills almost 17,000 Americans yearly while increasing Nexavar sales from $165 million last year. Currently, Nexavar is approved to treat kidney cancer. ``The results of this trial are a breakthrough in the management of this disease,&#39;&#39; said Joseph Llovet, a liver cancer specialist at Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York, and lead author of the study, in a telephone interview. ``For the first time, we have a drug that is working.&#39;&#39; The data should make Nexavar the new standard of care for inoperable liver cancer, said analyst Phil Nadeau of Cowen & Company, in a May 21 note. It will remain so ``for the next several years,&#39;&#39; because rivals are still in early stages of development, he wrote. The shares of Onyx, based in Emeryville, California, rose $2.64 to $33.52 at 4 p.m. New York time in Nasdaq Stock Market composite trading. Earlier, the stock reached $34. Bayer&#39;s shares closed 15 cents higher at 54.48 euros in Frankfurt. Onyx shares have almost tripled this year, and are the best-performing on the Nasdaq Biotechnology Index, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The study, in 602 patients, showed Nexavar is the first to show improved survival against liver cancer among about 100 that have completed involving other drugs over 30 years, Llovet said in an interview. Patients who have liver tumors now have them surgically removed if possible, or have radiation or chemotherapy delivered directly to the organ, researchers said. The most common side effects with Nexavar were diarrhea in 11 percent of patients, and swelling in the hands and feet for 8 percent of patients, researchers said. Side effects were similar to those for patients with kidney cancer, and the drug was ``very well tolerated,&#39;&#39; compared with chemotherapy, Llovet said. Researchers found the drug worked by slowing the spread of the disease. It took a median of 28 weeks before Nexavar patients had their disease spread, compared with 12 weeks for those on placebo, the study found. The drug didn&#39;t meet a pre-specified goal for improving quality of life, Llovet said. Nexavar is taken as an oral pill. It is a targeted therapy, which blocks proteins on cells, to stop tumor cells from proliferating and cut off the blood supply to tumors. ``For a new drug in the most advanced form of liver cancer, this is quite an impressive gain,&#39;&#39; said Nancy Davidson, an oncologist at Johns Hopkins Kimmel Cancer Center in Baltimore, in a news conference. The liver cancer trial is one of 45 Nexavar studies being highlighted at the cancer meeting in Chicago, said Hollings Renton, Onyx&#39;s Chief Executive Officer, in a telephone interview. Nexavar represents part of the company&#39;s strategy to pick a few tough-to-treat tumors, establish effectiveness and branch out by adding it in combinations with other therapies. The drug is also being studied in melanoma, lung and breast cancers. ``We have been successful beyond our wildest dreams,&#39;&#39; Renton said. Nexavar was first approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration in December 2005 for patients with advanced kidney cancer. The drug competes with Pfizer Inc.&#39;s Sutent, and costs users about $4,500 a month, the company has said. Onyx and Bayer each take half the profits from Nexavar worldwide, with the exception of Japan, where Bayer takes a greater share, Renton said. The commercial opportunity may be greater in Europe, where the disease is more than twice as common as in the U.S., Renton said. About 19,160 new cases of liver cancer will be diagnosed in the U.S. this year, with about 70 percent of them being men, according to the American Cancer Society. Liver cancer killed an estimated 598,000 people worldwide in 2002, according to the International Agency for Research on Cancer, in Lyon, France. Liver cancer is associated with Hepatitis B and C infection, and alcoholism, said Ghassan Abou-Alfa, a liver cancer specialist at Memorial Sloan-Kettering in New York, in an interview. More people may get the disease in the future because studies show obesity may play a role, he said. Some researchers believe the disease is difficult to treat because damaged livers can&#39;t tolerate enough chemotherapy, or that the liver might be breaking down the drug before it can work, he said. Nexavar may be working where others failed, because it works by blocking proteins involved in tumor proliferation, and that supply blood and nutrients to cancer cells, he said. To contact the reporters on this story: Luke Timmerman in San Francisco at ; Eva von Schaper in Munich at Last Updated: June 4, 2007 16:13 EDT Related Media on Demand Renton Sees Nexavar Approval for Liver Cancer by 2008 Baum of Pfizer Says Sutent May Treat Several Cancers German Stocks Beat Europe, Emerging Markets, Emulating &#39;60s Earnings Gains DAX Index Slides, Led by E.ON, Deutsche Bank, Siemens; ThyssenKrupp Rises European Stocks Drop, Paced by Banks on Downgrade; Deutsche Bank, BNP Fall
