http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-6&fd=R&url=http://www.edmondsun.com/local/local_story_153223622.html&cid=1116367587&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg The Edmond Sun, Edmond, OK - Edmond’s Relay for Life surpasses goal Mon, Jun 04 2007 CLICK FOR MORE WEATHER June 02, 2007 10:36 pm Edmond&#8217;s Relay for Life surpasses goal Special to The Sun About 35 cancer survivors helped kick off the 2007 Edmond Relay for Life with a survivor lap around the Hamilton Field House at the University of Central Oklahoma on Friday. The survivors carried pink, white and purple balloons as family and team members clapped and cheered in honor of their victories. Caregivers and children joined their parents and loved ones for a second lap. The survivors then went outside to release their balloons. A proud father carried survivor Isaac Newberry, 3-years-old, around the track. Suzy Shoemaker, Isaac&#8217;s aunt, said he was diagnosed with cancer when he was 1. &#8220;He&#8217;s cancer-free right now,&#8221; she said. Shoemaker, in charge of survivorship for the Relay for Life Committee, said more than 10 million people have battled cancer and survived. &#8220;This is the main reason we do Relay for Life,&#8221; she said. &#8220;From the day these people heard, &#8216;You have cancer,&#8217; they have been survivors.&#8221; She said the event was a night for people who have shared the same experiences to console and comfort each other. The Edmond Firefighters Association was one of two teams to raise more than $5,000 for the event. Firefighter Brad Powell said this is their first year to participate. &#8220;One of our firefighters just recovered 11 months ago and he&#8217;s been involved with this and we came out to support him,&#8221; Powell said. During the past four years, the Crusaders, another team, has raised a total of about $10,000 for Relay for Life. &#8220;My dad died of cancer 10 years ago,&#8221; said team captain Carrie Loper. She said the team is not representing a business or organization but represents a group of friends who have lost a total of three family members. &#8220;That&#8217;s what brought us together,&#8221; Loper said. While teams honored survivors and those who have died from cancer, many individual survivors also celebrated. Survivor David Dean, 77, was diagnosed with prostate cancer in 2002. He said the cancer measured 11.5 on a PSA before treatment and 0.29 after. &#8220;I was treated with radiation for 25 days,&#8221; he said. &#8220;I went five days a week for five weeks.&#8221; He said the hardest challenge of radiation for him was how frequently he had to go to the bathroom. He said he used to wake up three or four times a night to use the bathroom and now he frequently sleeps through the entire night. &#8220;There are just a lot of people out there who have cancer and are going to have cancer,&#8221; Dean said. Robbie Maroney is a second-year survivor of breast cancer. &#8220;(Relay for Life) is really important for me because of the progress they made,&#8221; she said. &#8220;I look forward to the day that there is no longer breast cancer.&#8221; To help raise more funds for Edmond Relay for Life, Mindy Lee sold purple and white stovepipe hats with the word &#8220;Hope&#8221; etched into them. Lee said the woman who created the hats lives in Tennessee and lost her sister and son to cancer. She created them with the intent that all proceeds be donated to Relay for Life fundraisers across the nation. Relay for Life is a fundraiser organized and created by the American Cancer Society. Deer Creek Rose Union Elementary students designed paper bags for luminaries. The bags were decorated to follow this year&#8217;s Relay for Life theme of &#8220;Around the World.&#8221; &#8220;Luminaries are to honor those who are fighting cancer or in remission and you buy them in memory of or in honor of someone,&#8221; said Jamie Nikkel, committee member. At 10 p.m., the luminaries were lit and the name for which each bag was purchased was read. The survivors then walked a lap of silence. Shoemaker said the Edmond Relay for Life raised a little more than $87,000, surpassing its $85,000 goal. Click to discuss this story with other readers on our forums. MAIKE SABOLICH/The Edmond Sun Edmond firefighter and cancer survivor Tim Vernon, right, gives Tammy Padgett a high five as she and others walk in the Relay for Life event at Hamilton Field House this Friday. (Click for larger image) More from the Local News section Derby lures first-time fishers Edmond&#8217;s Relay for Life surpasses goal City to add 19 staff Santa Fe grad heads to nationals North graduate helps document Uganda&#8217;s struggles Enter name or type of business Enter city & state, or zip code Local Search powered by PremierGuide Popular business directory searches DEVELOP JOBS FOR INDIVIDUALS W/DISABILITIES DEVELOP JOBS FOR INDIVIDUALS WITH DISABILITIES Great oppty to wk in a team environment w/ a large non-profit agency 3/2/2 w/opener, all kitchen equip, CH/A, fenced, W/D, FP. Very clean, no smoking, $695/mo, 826-8443 or 348-1261. It’s an exciting time to work at LMC. It’s an exciting time to work at LMC. Come be a part of our team! Central Scheduler – Full Busy NW Pediatric Office Busy NW pediatric office needs medical assistant for mainly front office F/T or P/T. Fax resume to 945-4991 CNHI Internet Sales Consultant CNHI Internet Sales Consultant Don’t miss an opportunity to be part of the exciting growth and innovation in PAYROLL CLERK Duit Construction, a heavy highway construction company located in Edmond, has an opening for a FT Payroll ACCOUNTS PAYABLE CLERK Duit Construction, a heavy highway construction company located in Edmond, has an opening for a F Kennel tech needed walking dogs, general pet care. Wkends & evenings a MUST. Immediate openings. 340-3808 LOOKING FOR A CAREER or A JOB? LOOKING FOR A CAREER or A JOB? If you are looking for an exciting career in media sales, please continue read Join Logan Medical C