http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-4&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/story.html%3Fid%3Da59ac0ae-157f-46cc-9bfd-ffcfb186c22c&cid=1116832274&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Cord blood now considered useful canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter canada.com where perspectives connect in the Leader Post Jobs in Regina working.com 10 year archive in FPinfomart See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter Find a job at working.com Find a car at driving.ca Find an apartment at renting.ca Find real estate at Homes Find great stuff at shopping Selling? Place an ad Meet a match at Connecting Headlines marked with a are exclusive to subscribers. Update credit card information Send us a news tip Setting a world record Mosaic was a chance for thousands to discover world traditions and an opportunity... Going after identity thieves Surfing for porn in Afghanistan 9/11 border security has little impact on trade; costs more Canada can't meet Kyoto targets: Harper Cottages, condos will be hot buys of the future: report Cord blood now considered useful Joanne Laucius, CanWest News Service Published:Â Saturday, June 02, 2007 OTTAWA -- About two dozen transplant specialists and representatives from patient groups are meeting in Ottawa this weekend to draw up plans for a Canadian bank for donated blood drawn from the umbilical cords of newborn babies. Cord blood, once considered medical waste, is now seen as a valuable tool in fighting leukemia, immune diseases and inherited blood diseases like sickle cell anemia, because it is rich in stem cells. Stem cells are uniquely able to develop into a wide variety of other highly specialized types of cells. Demand for cord blood transplants is expected to increase "exponentially," says hematologist Dr. Graham Sher, CEO at Canadian Blood Services, which has proposed setting up and managing a national cord-blood bank. Sher estimates such a project would cost about $4.5 million to set up and over $2 million per year to maintain. It currently costs about $25,000 US on the global market to purchase a cord blood sample for a transplant. Email to a friend There are two public cord-blood banks in Canada, in Montreal and Edmonton, housing only a few thousand samples. Some new parents are also paying private banks to store their children's cord blood, as insurance in case the child or a sibling ever develops a blood disease. Last year, 45 people in Canada were treated with stem cells from cord blood -- almost all of it from donors outside Canada. There are about 150,000 cord-blood samples held in 50 public blood banks around the world. Â© The Leader-Post (Regina) 2007 Scandal Sheet: Brad Pitt Brad Pitt was spotted in Montreal... Mexican crime won't stop Canadians Canadians took more trips abroad... Go topless this summer A sure sign of spring is the sight... Fox Sports World Canada Copyright & Permission Rules &copy; 2007 CanWest Interactive, a division of CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. . All rights reserved. Unauthorized distribution, transmission or republication strictly prohibited.
http://www.dogflu.ca/06042007/12/uw_receives_105_million_dollar_donation&cid UW Receives 105 Million Dollar Donation | DogFlu.ca Ontario Animal Shelter Contact Information Health Information for Human Beings Human Conditions and Diseases UW Receives 105 Million Dollar Donation It is being reported that the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation has donated 105 million dollars to the University of Washington to be used to creat a leading center of health program analysis and evaluation It is being reported that the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation has donated 105 million dollars to the University of Washington. The grant will be used in conjunction with an additional 20 million dollars supplied by the university and the government to creat the world's leading center of health program analysis and evaluation, a project that will be led by Dr. Christopher Murray, a widely known Harvard University economist. "In medicine, we would never think to sell a drug that had not been completely shown to be safe and effective," said Dr. Julio Frenk, a former health minister for Mexico who is now a senior adviser to the Gates Foundation. "Yet we often think nothing of launching some large-scale social or health intervention without first doing the same kind of rigorous study to accurately identify the problem and most likely solutions," Frenk added. The project will work by focusing on judging success or failure in global health practices and policies, whether by foundations, governments, corporations or private organization. "My foray into this area was motivated by frustration with a simple question: What are the biggest health problems in the world, and where are people with these problems living?" he asked. "The first thing I learned is that, in global health, everyone exaggerated the problem they were working on." "The history of development projects, not just in health, is littered with enormous investments that very often don't yield anything," he said. Murray states that it is very important that because of the great donations by organizations like the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, it is impairitive that their investments result in a positive outcome. "This represents a tremendous step forward for the university and for all of the global health community," said Dr. Pat Wahl, dean of the UW School of Public Health. Click Here to Join the Discussion! at 2007-06-04 16:02 | Copyright Â© 2006 DogFlu.Ca All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-1&fd=R&url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml%3Fxml%3D/news/2007/06/04/wsex04.xml&cid=1116865706&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg 'Sexsomnia' linked to sleep problems | International News | News | Telegraph 'Sexsomnia' linked to sleep problems Britain's No.1 quality newspaper website | Make us your homepage Monday 4 June 2007 'Sexsomnia' linked to sleep problems People with sleep disorders might also suffer from abnormal sexual behaviour, psychiatrists claim. Researchers believe that some chronic insomniacs also exhibit signs of a surge in libido and "compulsive sexual behaviours". Dr Carlos Schenck, a senior psychiatrist at the Minnesota Regional Sleep Disorders Centre in Minneapolis, led a study into "sexsomnia". He states that in some cases sexsomnia behaviour can be upsetting or frightening for the sleeper's partner. But, he added, many sufferers delay seeking help because they fear that doctors will not believe their behaviour is really unconscious. He said: "More reports are surfacing of abnormal sexual behaviours emerging during sleep. "While people may think this type of behaviour is humorous, in reality it can be a serious problem for some individuals and couples." Post this story to: Snoring may bring on Alzheimer's, say scientists Top economist fears Bank of England has lost control. Nancy Dell'Olio talks about her best and worst holidays. Hilary Alexander takes a look at the stars of future. Charles Spencer hails Patrick Stewart as Macbeth. &copy; Copyright of Telegraph Media Group Limited 2007. Terms & Conditions of reading. Privacy and Cookie Policy.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-0&fd=R&url=http://www.paulsvalleydailydemocrat.com/homepage/local_story_155105010.html%3Fkeyword%3Dleadpicturestory&cid=1116367587&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Pauls Valley, OK, Pauls Valley Daily Democrat - Luminaria plans underway Mon, Jun 04 2007 CLICK FOR MORE WEATHER June 04, 2007 10:50 am RFL ceremony to honor victims, survivors Next weekend crowds of people from every walk of life will gather at Thompson Field in Wacker Park to celebrate the 11th annual Garvin County Relay For Life. Festivities will kick off on Friday, June 8 with one of the main events of the evening being the luminaria ceremony, where cancer victims and survivors will be honored in a variety of special ways. &#8220;The luminaria ceremony will begin a little after dark and one of the ways we will be recognizing victims and survivors that night is by placing a luminaria bag along the track with their name on it,&#8221; said luminaria chairperson Janet Moore. &#8220;When the lights all go off, they create a soft glow around the track which really changes the atmosphere in the stadium. The luminaria bags are a really great way to honor friends and loved ones and they&#8217;re only $5 each.&#8221; Luminarias are not the only way that cancer victims and survivors will be recognized at this year&#8217;s Relay For Life. Moore said interested parties may also purchase a memorial &#8220;star&#8221; and, if they choose, have their loved one&#8217;s name and photo included in a special slide show presentation. &#8220;I want people to realize there are all kinds of ways to honor and remember those who have touched their lives in some way. As in years past, they can purchase a large star cut-out for $15 which will bear the name of the person they wish and it will be placed on the fence around the track near the stage area,&#8221; Moore explained. &#8220;In addition to the luminarias and the stars, we will also have a large screen set up near the stage this year where we will be showing slides of cancer victims and survivors. If you purchase a luminaria bag and a star, we will also add a slide for only $1 more,&#8221; she said. &#8220;If you would like to have a picture of someone &#8216;in memory of&#8217; or &#8216;in honor of&#8217; included in the slide show presentation, all you have to do is bring a scannable photo and their information by the Sonic office before the Relay so we will have plenty of time to include them.&#8221; Along with the traditional luminarias, stars and slides, Moore said she has added something new this year in which cancer victims and survivors may be shown special honor in a Polynesian fashion. &#8220;We&#8217;re trying something a little different this year where we will be selling tiki torches as a way to honor people at the Relay. They are $35 each and we&#8217;ll set them up around the track along with the luminaria bags,&#8221; Moore said. &#8220;There will be a sign on each one with the information about the honored individual and people can decorate them any way they want to. Then they can take them home after the Relay and next year they can use them again for a donation of only $25.&#8221; Moore noted all proceeds raised during this year&#8217;s Relay For Life will be donated to the American Cancer Society, which has dedicated itself to diminishing the suffering caused from cancer and eliminating cancer altogether through research, education, advocacy and service. For more information on this week&#8217;s Garvin County Relay For Life or to purchase a luminaria, star, slide or tiki torch, call Janet Moore at 405-238-7594 or go by the Sonic office located at 517 S. Willow in Pauls Valley. Click to discuss this story with other readers on our forums. Cancer survivors wear the traditional purple T-shirts during last year&#8217;s Garvin County Relay For Life. This year&#8217;s Relay event is scheduled to get underway at 7 p.m. Friday, June 8 at Thompson Field in Pauls Valley&#8217;s Wacker Park. (PVDD file photo) (Click for larger image) More from the Homepage section City to close Indian Meridian Monday County office plans get a look Wettest May in a decade Businesses taking heat over high gas prices Enter name or type of business Enter city & state, or zip code Local Search powered by PremierGuide Popular business directory searches Are you a company driver? Tired of making money for the other guy? Revolutionary new program. Business consultant to help Are you a company driver? Are you a company driver? Tired of making money for the other guy? Pauls Valley Health Care Pauls Valley Health Care Facility is taking applications for a dietary cook. Would prefer experience with menus, bu Girling Health Care, Inc. Girling Health Care, Inc. $100.00 Sign on Bonus Now accepting applications for Vocational Program Coordinator in the Wayne area. Must have HS Diploma or GED, clean Post Office Now hiring Post Office now hiring Avg. Pay $20/hr or $57K annually including Federal Benefits and OT Paid Owner Operators, Fleet Owners, Owner Operators, Fleet Owners, First-Time Buyers. Dedicated carrier for the nation's largest retailer Pauls Valley General Hospital Pauls Valley General Hospital Maintenance Department is hiring for a full time grounds keeper. See Doug Washita Valley Living Center Washita Valley Living Center We are seeking an LPN for weekend doubles. 6am-2pm and 2pm-10pm. Work 32 hours an Drivers: Regional Carrier: Home/weekends. 05 & Newer peterbilts, Newer flatbeds. Recent Pay increase, insuranc ••SELL YOUR CAR HERE•• Sell your car here. Call Wendy or Christie at 405-238-6464 for more information **SELL YOUR HOME HERE** Sell your home here in our Premium Homes Section. Call Wendy at 238-6464 for more information. Got Land? Have Family land? 9 homes available for special financing program. 0 down, $136.90 every 2 Zero Down if own land or use family land. Bad credit ok. We own the Bank. Use your land or family land (size does not matter) Free Del/setup, 