http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070604/heely_sneakers_070604/20070604%3Fhub%3DTopStories&cid CTV.ca | Docs blame rash of injuries on 'heeling' sneakers CTV News with Lloyd Robertson Docs blame rash of injuries on 'heeling' sneakers Updated Mon. Jun. 4 2007 12:13 PM ET Children may love "heelys" -- those trendy sneakers with the wheels inside that let kids zip around -- but doctors warn the shoes are leading to a host of injuries that are sending kids to the emergency room. Roller shoes are a popular type of sneaker with a convertible or removable wheel in the heel. The innovative shoes allow "heelers" to go from a walk to a roll by simply shifting their body weight. The most popular brand, Heelys, was first launched in 2000 in the United States, and are now sold in 70 countries. Street Gliders are a similar version in which wheels are strapped to regular running shoes. The devices also allow users to combine walking with rolling by simply shifting body weight. According to a study published in the journal , the orthopedic department of one hospital in Dublin, Ireland, saw 67 children admitted over 10 weeks last summer for injuries suffered while using "roller shoes." Interestingly, most of those injured -- 56 of them -- were girls. The most common location of injuries were in the arms, wrists and shoulders and included fractures and dislocations. None of the injured children had been using protective gear when injured. More than half of the injuries occurred the first time the child used his or her roller shoes or while learning to use them. The children were aged anywhere from 6.2 to 14.9 years, with a mean age of 9.6 years. Despite their injuries, 54 per cent of the children said they would continue "heeling" or "street gliding" after they recovered. The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission says several injuries have been reported in the United States as well, including at least one death related to the shoes. The Canadian Safety Council issued a consumer alert in January 2006 advising children and parents of children using Heelys to wear protective gear and to avoid heeling on roads, sidewalks, and wet surfaces. They recommended a ban on heeling in public buildings and malls, as well as school hallways and playgrounds. The safety council estimates that a month with daily practice is required to master the "heeling" technique, to learn to control and balance of the body's centre of gravity. The study authors recommend close supervision during the learning curve and use of protective gear at all times. "Wrist guards should always be worn to reduce impact forces and distribution when a child falls on the outstretched hand, because upper-limb trauma constitutes 86.5% of our cases," the authors note. Last April, Heelys said a study it commissioned shows that their shoes have a safer injury rate than skateboarding, inline skating and even swimming. The company notes that the shoes are sold with safety information including a recommendation to wear protective gear. Divorce increases risk of Ritalin use, study finds Antipsychotics increase death risk among seniors Ecstasy harms language-related memory, study finds EU launches campaign to tackle back pain Feds want stricter controls on 17 toxic substances Canadian Blood Services to seek $5M from provinces Cape Breton doctor suspended by medical college Media frenzy over TB traveller muffles warnings Docs blame rash of injuries on 'heeling' sneakers CTV Newsnet: Wheeled shoes sending kids to E.R. Study in Pediatrics journal Canada Safety Council on Heelys
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-5&fd=R&url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/article/%3Fid%3D318383%26type%3DFeature&cid=1116867696&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Skin protection vital in sunny season -- Shanghai Daily | ä¸Šæµ·æ—¥æŠ¥ -- English Window to China News Tuesday, 5 June, 2007 Charity and civil affairs Crime and public security Expat association and community Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macau affairs Accounting, auditing and taxation Precious metals and gems China business travel forum Food & Hospitality Expo Golf, Travel & Lifestyle Skin protection vital in sunny season http://www.shanghaidaily.com/article/?id=318383&type=Feature Skin protection vital in sunny season Incidental sun exposure is no small matter. As little as 20 minutes of casual sun exposure each day adds up to more than 120 hours of UV radiation annually. That equals five days of serious sunbathing. Whether exposed for five minutes or five hours, incidental amounts of sun exposure can contribute to lines and wrinkles, alterations in the skin's natural defense system, discoloration and uneven tone. According to Clinique's guiding dermatologist, Dr David Orentriech, the sun accounts for approximately 90 percent of the aging appearance. Only 10 percent is due to actual number of years lived. If a person can minimize the daily dose of incidental sun exposure, she will reduce the single most important factor to the appearance of aging. To minimize daily sun damage, using a proper sunscreen product each morning as the last step in facial treatment prior to any makeup application is absolutely necessary. Sunscreen protects from ultraviolet rays that cause a wrinkled, leathery look and possibly skin cancer. But from years of clinical research and countless consultations with dermatologists, Clinique has found the number one skin mistake that most people make is not wearing sunscreen - or in wearing it incorrectly. Skincare manufacturers always proclaim the importance of wearing sunscreen. However, with so many sunblock creams on the market working in different ways, a little knowledge of the product and its correct usage is essential. Based on their mechanism of action, sunscreens can broadly be classified into two groups - chemical absorbers and physical blockers. Chemical absorbers work by absorbing ultraviolet radiation and can be further differentiated by the type of radiation they absorb, UVA or UVB, or both. Physical blockers work by reflecting or scattering UV radiation. SPF stands for Sun Protection Factor and is the system used worldwide to determine how much protection a sunscreen provides. A sunscreen with SPF of 15 provides 93.6 percent protection against UVB. Protection against UVB is increased to 94.3 percent with SPF of 25, according to Clinique global research. SPF 15 will protect you for 2 1/2 hours while SPF 30 will protect for five hours in theory. However, the effectiveness of a sunscreen has more to do with how much is applied, how often it is applied, whether the person is sweating heavily and being exposed to water. It is recommended to apply sunscreen every two hours. When choosing a bottle, make sure you look for the words broad spectrum, as SPF only refers to UVB rays. Skin needs to be protected from UVA rays (the cause of premature aging and skin cancer) too. A proper broad-spectrum sunscreen should contain avobenzone, titanium dioxide or zinc oxide for significant UVA protection. Clinique City Block Sheer SPF 25 (250 yuan (US$32.68)/40 milliliters) The skincare giant's new City Block Sheer SPF 25, a lightweight, subtly tinted, oil-free addition to the City Block family, is even easier to layer and more sheer on skin than before. New to the formula are moisture-wicking fibers and a specific extract sourced from algae that helps reduce excess oil on the skin's surface. It also helps in repelling perspiration and in making makeup stay put. This 100 percent physical (non-chemical) formula provides powerful antioxidants and anti-irritants that Clinique's City Block line is known for. Cleansing with a makeup remover is strongly suggested. Elizabeth Arden Ceramide Plump Perfect Moisture Cream SPF 30 (710 yuan/48 grams) This all-in-one state-of-the-art treatment and moisturizer surrounds skin with everything needed for a plumper and relaxed look with less lines. Most importantly, SPF 30 helps protect from the aging effects of the sun. It should be smoothed onto a cleansed face and neck daily before sun exposure. Guerlain Brightening High Protection SPF 50 PA+++ (500 yuan/30 ml) This highly-effective fluid provides skin with maximum UVA and UVB protection in addition to the other active ingredients in the range. Its perspiration-resistant texture protects the face from external aggressions. Apply gently in the morning with fingers. La Mer The SPF 18 Fluid (750 yuan/50 ml) Just as plants need sunlight to thrive, there are energies within the light spectrum necessary for well-being. Utilizing this principle, The SPF 18 Fluid captures beneficial light while diverting potentially damaging light. The product provides a trio of natural and sea-derived ingredients that uniquely benefit skin. Gemstones absorb light energy, transforming it into beneficial green light to enhance antioxidant activity. Photonic spheres within redirect and diffuse light. Smart, light-reactive seaweeds impart natural humectant properties and bind moisture to prevent dehydration. Worn over Creme de la Mer, the fluid acts as a generator, actually boosting its efficacy. Sisley Sunleya (1,600 yuan/50 ml) Sunleya contains a specific UVA/UVB filtering complex capable of blocking out 90 percent of sunrays; it only allows the right amount of rays to help the skin deploy its own natural photo-protection reflexes. Instead of artificially blocking the arrival of melanin and the thickening of the stratum corneum - what a "total sunblock" would do - Sunleya allows both processes to gradually deploy on the skin's surface in order to fulfill their essential defense function. Fancl SunGuard 30 (for face and body) (228 yuan/60 ml) This product is preservative-free and gentle to skin. It contains no UV absorbents, but provides a high level of long-lasting protection against harmful UV rays. It smoothens on skin easily without leaving white residues, while providing a moisturizing effect. It is also resistant to water, perspiration and sebum. It is highly recommended for sport and leisure time. It can also be used as a makeup base. Estee Lauder Cyber White UV Defense SPF 30/PA++ (425 yuan/50 ml) This protective base safeguards skin out of UVA/UVB and environmental pollution. The antioxidation gene will fight against the violation of freeradicals. Along with the "Resvertrol" that may enhance the effect of whitening and moisturizing, the base feels light on the face and makes skin brighter.a M.A.C Prep + Prime Face Protect SPF 50/PA++ (360 yuan/30 ml) Apply this skin-protecting cream with SPF 50 under makeup to prime the skin for the sun. It is featherweight, fast-absorbing, oil-free, and invisible; it will not affect the look, texture or long wear integrity of the makeup. Specially formulated with oil-absorbing powder, it helps prevent oil breakthrough and provides a high-level, broad spectrum sun protection. Bobbi Brown SPF 50/PA++ Protective Face Base (550 yuan/50 ml) This face base is a lightweight, invisible UV protector with SPF 50/PA++ that works beautifully under all types of Bobbi Brown makeup without altering color. It contains sebum-absorbing powders that provide excellent oil-absorbing benefits and sucrose and caffeine that calms skin as the formula protects against environmental aggressors. This breathable cream is non-greasy, easily-absorbed and blends smoothly into skin. Click the button to copy the title and the URL of this story. Shanghai Daily Home | Copyright Â© 2001-2007 Shanghai Daily Publishing House
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-0&fd=R&url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200706030015.html&cid=1116924013&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg allAfrica.com: Africa: EU Commits 400 Mln. Euros to HIV/Aids Global Fund (Page 1 of 1) Use our pull-down menus to find more stories São Tomé and Príncipe Asia, Australia, and Africa Latin America and Africa Middle East and Africa U.S., Canada and Africa Enter your search terms Africa: EU Commits 400 Mln. Euros to HIV/Aids Global Fund Posted to the web 3 June 2007 European Commission President Jose Manuel Barroso Thursday pledged 100 million euro about 134 million U.S. dollars for the HIV/AIDS global fund for 2007, and proposed a further 300 million euros about 403 million dollars over the following three years, Xinhua reported from Brussels. Barroso made the commitment at a meeting with top leaders of the Global Fund to fight HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria. He said "the European Commission is one of the leaders in the global fight against HIV/AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria. This pledge keeps us there. It is part of the European Union&#39;s commitment to the poorest and most vulnerable, in terms of aid, trade and political support." The European Commission has provided 522 million euro, about 702 million dollars, to the fund over the past five years. So far programmes supported by the global fund have saved approximately 1.8 million lives. Currently, an estimated 3,000 additional lives are being saved per day, through providing AIDS treatment for 1.1 million people, tuberculosis treatment for 2.8 million, as well as effective medicines for 23 million cases of malaria, and distributing bed nets to 30 million families in Africa and elsewhere. Meanwhile, President Bush has asked the US Congress to set aside 30 billion US dollars over five years for the global fight against HIV/AIDS, BBC reported. He said the sum would double the current US commitment and provide treatment for 2.5 million people. The funding would also be aimed at preventing over 12 million new infections. United Nations agencies said about 40 million people worldwide are infected with HIV/AIDS. Two-third of those live in sub-Saharan Africa and almost three-quarter of deaths from HIV/AIDS last year also occurred there. The number of peple has increased everywhere, with the most striking increases in East Asia and Central Asia/Eastern Europe, it was indicated. The World Health Organization (WHO) Wednesday urged affected countries to carry out HIV tests on everyone attending health centres unless they "opt out". &copy; 2007 Ethiopian Herald. All rights reserved. Distributed by AllAfrica Global Media ( ). To contact the copyright holder directly for corrections -- or for permission to republish or make other authorized use of this material, aggregates and indexes content from over 125 African news organizations , plus more than , who are responsible for their own reporting and views. Articles and commentaries that identify as the publisher are produced or commissioned by AllAfrica Make allAfrica.com your home page Decent Work Agenda Instrumental for Renaissance, Says President of Ghana G-8 Commitments to Continent are Behind Schedule Pact to End Use of Children in War ActionAid Damns Finance Ministers Drug-Resistant AIDS - The Next Tsunami
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-4&fd=R&url=http://www.medicalnewstoday.com/medicalnews.php%3Fnewsid%3D72849&cid=1116719749&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg International Pharmaceutical Federation Supports WHO Action To Promote Smoke-Free Environments if (screen.width > 1000) document.write(' - Health News - Smoking / Quit Smoking News International Pharmaceutical Federation Supports WHO Action To Promote Smoke-Free Environments Smoking / Quit Smoking News Article Date: 02 Jun 2007 - 1:00 PDT email to a friend view or write opinions Article Also Appears In Pharma Industry / Biotech Industry Today the World Health Organization is urging all across the globe to recognize and participate in World No Tobacco Day, held annually on May 31. This year the event will centre around the theme , with WHO and associated stakeholders promoting this method as the ONLY effective measure to protect individuals - including women, children, and those sharing a public or workspace â€" from exposure to and risk of second-hand smoke. There has been a recent upsurge of global awareness of the need for tobacco-free environments, with many countries passing legislation to ban smoking in all public areas. This comes as a drastic change from times past when smoking was a social norm. FIP wholeheartedly supports WHO and partner efforts in controlling the use of tobacco in public areas through adopting smoke-free environments in all FIP related meetings, Congresses, activities and at Headquarters. WHO reports that tobacco is the second major cause of death in the world, with the over 650 million global smokers eventually succumbing to the ills of tobacco use. Furthermore, and perhaps more devastating, hundreds of thousands of individuals die every year from disease related to exposure to second-hand smoke. FIP IN ACTION - At Home and Around the World In addition to promoting 100% tobacco-free environments throughout Federation activities, FIP has made great strides in raising awareness of the devastating risks of tobacco use, and how pharmacists around the world can play an integral part in curbing tobacco use and encouraging smoking cessation. Through the development of the Global Network of Pharmacists Against Tobacco ( ), which aims to increase communication and interaction between professionals working towards increasing the role of the pharmacist in anti-tobacco activities and the joint tobacco-free declarations with multi-disciplinary partners in the World Health Professions Alliance, FIP is making it a priority to involve pharmacists in every step in the shared vision for a smoke-free world. To showcase this philosophy, this year the 67th FIP World Congress of Pharmacy and Pharmaceutical Sciences ( ) will host a half day Session on Curbing the Tobacco Pandemic - The Role of the Pharmacist . The Session will provide a global perspective, welcoming speakers from all areas who will bring to light the widespread threat of tobacco use and also how pharmacists may best play a role in harm reduction and patient support. A variety of worldwide examples will be showcased, with topics focusing on the threat of the global smoking pandemic and the role of pharmacists in its control, health impacts of tobacco use in China, enhancing pharmacists' skills, to name but a few. Through these ongoing initiatives, FIP is dedicated to fighting tobacco use on global level, and encourages all Members, pharmacists and pharmaceutical scientists to be actively involved in these endeavours. International Pharmaceutical Federation (FIP) FIP is a world-wide federation of national pharmaceutical (professional and scientific) associations, with a mission to represent and serve pharmacy and pharmaceutical sciences around the globe. Through its member associations, FIP connects, represents and serves more a million pharmacists and pharmaceu-tical scientists around the world. FIP was founded in The Hague, The Netherlands, in 1912 and still has its central office in The Hague. Although FIP is a federation of associations, any pharmacist or pharmaceutical scientist can apply to become an Individual Member of FIP. FIP is more than ninety years old. As an organisation, it has taken on new activities over the years and has grown in size. FIP works with its members in mind and is implementing positive changes to better serve its members. FIP activities are designed to improve the long-term effectiveness of patient care. It has actively worked towards the WHO goal of health for all, and intends to continue to do so. Do you want to become involved with the world of pharmacy and pharmaceutical sciences? Do you want to find out more about FIP? Then contact us. - View the latest Smoking / Quit Smoking News latest medical news headlines - Get medical news headlines weekly with our - Huge database of Contact Our Medical News Editors For any corrections of factual information, or to contact the editors please use our Please send any medical news or health news press releases to: Back to front page List of All Medical Articles Web design by Alastair Hazell Smoking / Quit Smoking Acid Reflux / GERD Alcohol / Addiction / Illegal Drugs Bird Flu / Avian Flu Cervical Cancer / HPV Vaccine CJD / vCJD / Mad Cow Disease Clinical Trials / Drug Trials Complementary Medicine / Alternative Medicine Cosmetic Medicine / Plastic Surgery Ear, Nose and Throat Erectile Dysfunction / Premature Ejaculation Eye Health / Ophthalmology Flu / Cold / SARS Health Insurance / Medical Insurance Immune System / Vaccines Infectious Diseases / Bacteria / Viruses IT / Internet / E-mail Liver Disease / Hepatitis Medical Malpractice / Litigation Medicare / Medicaid / Tricare MRI / PET / Ultrasound MRSA / Drug Resistance Muscular Dystrophy / ALS Obesity / Weight Loss / Fitness Pediatrics / Children's Health Pharma / Biotech Industry Primary Care / General Practice Prostate / Prostate Cancer Radiology / Nuclear Medicine Sexual Health / STDs Sleep / Sleep Disorders Smoking / Quit Smoking S