http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-4&fd=R&url=http://www.france24.com/france24Public/en/administration/afp-news.html%3Fid%3D070604155957.vjm8z9qf%26cat%3Dnull&cid=1116954432&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg La Cha&icirc;ne de l'Actualit&eacute; Internationale - Page d'accueil The week in Review Monday, June 4, 2007 Gates Foundation, university launch global health initiative A new initiative to evaluate global health care programs was launched Monday by the University of Washington with a 105-million-dollar grant from the Bill Melinda Gates Foundation. The funding, matched with 20 million dollars from the public university in the northwest state, will create a new Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation to conduct "independent, rigorous evaluations of health programs worldwide." The goal is to help guide international policymaking by analyzing health needs and outcomes, and assessing the performance of health programs, the university said. "Health policy must be based on evidence, not speculation," said Tachi Yamada, president of the Gates Foundation's Global Health Program. "There has been a huge increase in resources for global health in recent years, and it's essential to evaluate the impact of these investments. With high-quality data, we can ensure resources go where they are needed most, and dramatically improve health care delivery." UW President Mark Emmert said the Gates grant, the largest private gift in the school's history, "will enable us to bring unparalleled talent and resources to bear on the world's greatest health challenges." The new institute will be directed by Christopher Murray, who was previously director of the Harvard University Initiative for Global Health, and is a former senior official at the World Health Organization (WHO). The institute will focus on three main areas: health monitoring, including the prevalence of major diseases and the availability of health services; evaluation of the effectiveness of existing health programs; and dissemination of health data and information to decision-makers, researchers, and the public. "We hope to set the gold standard for scientifically rigorous evaluation in health," said Murray. "Global health spending is on the rise, yet too often there are gaps in information about where these funds can have the greatest impact." Murray said the institute will play a key role in helping achieve global health targets such as the Millennium Development Goals, which call for major improvements in health by 2015. Back to News Briefs Back to the top France 24 - Send by e-mail * Your name : * E-mail address (use commas to separate multiple addresses) : France 24 - Send by e-mail The article has successfully been sent by email Â© 2007 AFP - Bill Gates, is seen here in April 2007. A new initiative to evaluate global health care programs was launched Monday by the University of Washington with a 105-million-dollar grant from the Bill Melinda Gates Foundation. Â© 2007 AFP - Make France24.com your homepage Bramble and Sibierski join Wigan... Wigan have made a double raid on Newcastle United to snap up centre-back Titus Bramble and French forward Antoine Sibierski... New blow to Spector defense in... Music producer Phil Spector was dealt a blow in his murder trial here Monday when the judge refused to admit as evidence... US Democratic lawmaker charged... US Democratic Representative William Jefferson, who allegedly stashed 90,000 dollars in his freezer, was Monday indicted... Britain prepares exhibition of... The Design Museum in London announced Monday it will host next year an exhibition of the work of British architect Richard... Nigerian sues US group Pfizer over... The Nigerian government Monday filed a lawsuit asking for seven billion dollar damages from Pfizer over a drug test in which... Prosecutors demand top penalties... French prosecutors on Monday called for the maximum fine against oil group Total SA and tough sanctions for the manager and... Pamela Anderson 