http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-2&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/gates-fills-ellisons-funding-void/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257B02AE7429-F2FE-4843-BEE8-6EEA584E50D9%257D&cid=1116954432&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Gates fills Ellison's funding void for health center - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Gates fills Ellison's funding void for health center Last Update: 3:38 PM ET Jun 4, 2007 SAN FRANCISCO (MarketWatch) -- In a case of one tech mogul's deep pockets filling in for another's, Microsoft Corp. Chairman Bill Gates will help create a health research institute left without funding when Oracle Corp. Chief Executive Larry Ellison withdrew support roughly one year ago. The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation said Monday it will contribute $105 million to help fund the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation at the University of Washington, which will "conduct independent, rigorous evaluations of health programs worldwide." The institute will be directed by Dr. Christopher Murray, the Gates Foundation said. Before withdrawing support in the summer of 2006, Ellison intended to give $115 million to Harvard University to fund a similar institute, also to be run by Dr. Murray. cited the resignation of Harvard president Lawrence Summers, with whom Ellison had negotiated the contribution, as the reason for Ellison's decision to withdraw support. The UW's Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation will monitor the spread of diseases worldwide, evaluate the effectiveness of health programs and help make health information widely available, the Gates Foundation said in a release. The UW's institute will be funded primarily by the Gates Foundation grant, with an additional $20 million coming from the university. It will employ some 100 faculty and staff when it is fully operational. The Gates Foundation grant "is the largest private gift in UW's history," UW President Mark Emmert said in the release. The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation was formed in 2000, with the merger of the William H. Gates Foundation and the Gates Learning Foundation. Gates is expected to depart from his full-time position with Microsoft in mid-2008 in order to focus more on his philanthropic work. John Letzing is a MarketWatch reporter based in San Francisco. Related Blog Posts & Articles Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Sign up to receive the Weekend TV Show Preview U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 U.S. stock futures drop with bond yield rise, China in focus Five little-known tips for getting better gas mileage Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Three safe havens to stash your cash Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Palm sells stake to Elevation; former Apple execs join ranks Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Six common pitfalls to avoid as you start your small business Buy oil and mining companies, not commodities, ETF analyst says Three safe havens to stash your cash Who has the hot hand? Flextronics to acquire Solectron for $3.6 bln DRAM chipmakers to suffer worst quarter since 2001 Telecom firm Avaya reportedly close to private-equity deal Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 More equity hedge funds are shorting ETFs rather than stocks Shanghai tumbles 8.3% on concern about more cooling moves Investors embrace Wal-Mart's strategy change; shares gain Relations with Russia to overshadow Group of Eight summit U.S. stocks rise slightly after Shanghai stumble Apple puts a date on the iPhone rollout: June 29 Crude rallies on rising demand, Gulf storm, Russia Get the Latest MarketWatch News >> Company: Oracle Co