http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-6&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2007-06-04-liver-cancer_N.htm&cid=1116946098&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Kidney drug is first to buy time for liver cancer patients - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Your Health: Kim Painter Sign up to receive our free Daily Briefing e-newsletter and get the top news of the day in your inbox. Breaking news E-mail alerts Get breaking news in your inbox as it happens WHAT'S NEW IN THE BATTLE AGAINST CANCER? Top cancer researchers are gathered at the American Society of Clinical Oncology annual meeting in Chicago. USA TODAY's rounds up the latest findings: Alternative medicine: Ginseng may relieve patients' fatigue Lung cancer: Radiating the brain found to stop spread of tumors Shark cartilage flounders; flaxseed shows promise Liver cancer: Kidney drug buys time Breast cancer: Black women lag in survival Kidney drug is first to buy time for liver cancer patients By Liz Szabo, USA TODAY A newly approved kidney cancer drug has become the first chemotherapy to help patients with advanced liver tumors live longer &#8212; a finding expected to change the way patients are treated, researchers announced today. Liver tumors rarely spread to other organs. But by the time they are diagnosed, most have spread too far around the liver to be removed surgically, says William Li, president of the Angiogenesis Foundation, which funds research on tumor blood vessels. He was not involved in the new study. About 40% of liver cancers are diagnosed at an advanced stage, according to the American Society of Clinical Oncology. By that point, treatments &#8212; such as heating or freezing the tumor &#8212; aren't very effective, Li says. More than 19,000 people are diagnosed each year, and nearly 17,000 die. That's why doctors are excited about Nexavar, a pill first approved for kidney cancer in 2005, says Josep Llovet of Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York, lead author of the new study. In an international study of 602 patients with hepatocellular carcinoma, the most common type of liver cancer, doctors randomly assigned half to take Nexavar and half to get placebos. Those who took Nexavar lived a median of 10.7 months, while those on placebo survived 7.9 months, according to Llovet's paper, presented at the oncology society meeting in Chicago. Nexavar doesn't cure cancer. And, as the results show, patients on average lived less than a year, Llovet says. "It's not a terribly long time to live, but we have to consider that we are here with a devastating disease," Llovet says. "We are increasing survival 44%. It's a huge impact considering that we are targeting a very advanced tumor." Llovet holds out hope that Nexavar could offer an even greater benefit when combined with surgery in patients with less advanced cancers. Nexavar belongs to new class of "targeted" therapies that are designed to slow tumor growth, but cause fewer harsh side effects than traditional chemo, which can lead to dangerously low blood counts and infections. Llovet expects Nexavar to become the new standard of care. Because it is already approved for kidney tumors, liver cancer patients could get access to the drug off-label immediately, he says. Onyx and Bayer Pharmaceuticals, which market Nexavar, financed the trial. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
http://www.huffingtonpost.com/matthew-kavanagh/bush-on-aids-smoke-and-m_b_50618.html&cid Matthew Kavanagh: Bush On AIDS: Smoke and Mirrors, and Broken Promises - Politics on The Huffington Post Bush On AIDS: Smoke and Mirrors, and Broken Promises Posted June 4, 2007 "Bush Seeks to Double Spending for AIDS Program" blared the headlines this week . "President Bush should be commended," trumpeted one development organization, for his "vital leadership." Great... except that Bush's plan ISN'T going to double funding and his press conference was essentially called to spin major broken promises into looking like leadership. Too bad so many took the bait. In 2003, after a major campaign by activists across the US and around the world, Bush took a historic step in announcing the $15 billion, 5 year President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief or PEPFAR. The US went from spending a few hundred million dollars to putting up billions. And those billions have leveraged billions--countries around the world increased their funding for AIDS along with the US and we made a big leap toward truly addressing the pandemic. Those billions matter--with literally millions of people who will live because of the treatment, prevention, and care that has been mobilized by the global focus on turning the tide against AIDS. But this week showed that when we aren't pushing them hard, the administration will fall back into big talk and glitzy announcements that do little to help poor people living with HIV and AIDS. Bush's so-called "doubling" of AIDS funding actually reflects only a tiny increase that's hardly worthy of the world's wealthiest nation. By design the PEPFAR program has scaled up its spending each year--and is actually set to spent billions more than the original plan trying to keep pace with the AIDS pandemic. This year, for example, the White House requested $5.4 billion for global AIDS. Simply continuing this rate for the next five years would give us $27 billion--meaning Bush is asking for an increase of at most about $3 billion over 5 years (a rate that's actually dramatically slower than our current increases that are failing to keep up with the crisis). Really, then, this week's headlines should have read, "Bush asks Congress to stop increasing AIDS funding so quickly." This is at a moment when the pandemic is growing at a rate that far outpaces our resources to cope. More people were infected with HIV last year than the year before, which in turn was more than the year before that. The Global Fund to Fight AIDS, TB, and Malaria, meanwhile, is billions of dollars short of what it needs to do its work--and this year the President has proposed decreasing the US contribution by hundreds of millions of dollars. What's even more disturbing than the basic dollars, though, is that the President this week declared that he'd like to completely disregard the promise he made in 2005. That year, at the G8 meeting in Scotland, Bush and the other G8 leaders to ensure universal access to AIDS treatment by 2010. In the first five years of PEPFAR the goal was to fund treatment for 2 million people--a goal they may get near depending on how you count it. That's about 1/3 of the people in immediate need--which is a just goal since the US controls 1/3 of the global wealth. But apparently over the next 5 years Bush wants us to give up on the promise of Universal Access. As he got ready for this year's G8, the President suggested that the US should only fund programs to treat Â½ million more people. Meaning that, as we move from 6 million people to likely 9 or 10 million people who will need treatment, the US will be helping a smaller and smaller percentage of those in need. This kind of promise breaking is unworthy of our praise, to say the least. The real fair US contribution to a global AIDS response over the next 5 years is more like . Besides being less than US consumers will spent on bottled water over that 5 months worth of war So let's be clear--Bush wants to claim the mantle of global leadership on HIV/AIDS while basically suggesting that the US should do less of its share in the fight. Luckily for people living with HIV and AIDS, he's not the one in charge of appropriating money. Looks like it's up to Congress to rescue the US role on AIDS. Our organization, the Student Global AIDS Campaign , and others will be making sure they step up, but that'd be a lot easier if everyone would stop buying the smoke and mirrors act. Read All Posts by Jamie Lincoln Kitman: Chrysler At The Gates Of Hell Rumor Control: Spinning the Travoltas Anastasia Goodstein: The 'Porn Effect' Online Michelle Pilecki: Requiescat in Pace Al Franken: If You Ever Wonder Whether We Really Need Public Financing of Elections in this Country Roller Shoes Craze Spins Out Of Control Let The Mania Begin! IPhone Sets A Date Fmr Bush-Cheney Aides, Supporters Flock To Thompson Campaign Game Over? Murdoch To Meet With Bancrofts, Won't Cede Editorial Oversight "Knocked Up" A Knockout with $30M Debut, Demi Flops Advertise on Huffington Post Login to Huffington Post Make Huff Post your Home Page Copyright &copy; 2007 HuffingtonPost.com, Inc. Powered by Movable Type Your friend's email address: (Separate multiple addresses with commas.) Your friend's screen name:
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-4&fd=R&url=http://www.thebostonchannel.com/asseenon5/13439782/detail.html&cid=1116950771&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg At-Home Test Detects Fertility Trouble - As Seen On NewsCenter 5 Story - WCVB Boston As Seen On 5 As Seen On NewsCenter 5 At-Home Test Detects Fertility Trouble Screening Available For Men And Women POSTED: 3:49 pm EDT June 4, 2007 UPDATED: 4:13 pm EDT June 4, 2007 One out of every seven couples in the United States that is trying to get pregnant struggles to conceive. NewsCenter 5's Heather Unruh reported Monday that a Needham company has a test men and women can do at home that could be the first way to detect fertility trouble. "A year passed and I started getting like something's wrong here," Alba Garcia said. The Garcias tried to get pregnant for a year. But now, couples can find out if they have fertility problems in a matter of minutes with a new at-home fertility screening test. Fertell is new. The kit includes a female test that can detect a hormone level measuring egg production. It's conducted much like an at home pregnancy test and can be read in 30 minutes. "The FSH test that we do in our office -- that's actually in this kit -- is the first test we look for when a woman comes for an evaluation," Columbia University Medical Center's Dr. Harry Fisch said. For men, there's a test that measures the concentration of moving sperm -- a key indicator of sperm health. Results take 80 minutes, but the tests won't catch every fertility problem. "This test is not a guarantee that you're fertile or not. But it's a great start," Fisch said. Genosis is a company based in Needham. They say clinical trials showed their at-home fertility tests are 95 percent accurate. The Garcias finally sought help from a fertility specialist, and now, they have a daughter. But for them, this test would have been a godsend. "It would save me a year of not knowing we had a problem," Garcia said. Copyright 2007 by TheBostonChannel