http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-4&fd=R&url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/03/AR2007060300904.html&cid=1116966406&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Balancing Medical Risks - washingtonpost.com Find Bars & Clubs House Majority Leader Tom DeLay Indicted The FDA needs more authority to monitor drugs following their approval. Monday, June 4, 2007; Page A14 FOR YEARS, there have been rumblings that GlaxoSmithKline's diabetes drug, Avandia, might be associated with an increased risk of heart attack or other cardiovascular events. Also for years, the drug's labels have noted the risk. Then last month, the New England Journal of Medicine published a review of the available studies on Avandia's side effects that concluded that taking the medication can significantly boost patients' chances of experiencing heart trouble. Washington responded with a familiar fit of hypertension. In the space of a few days, congressional hearings had been scheduled, the Food and Drug Administration was under attack for being sloppy and slow, and the advocacy group Public Citizen was calling for the FDA to ban Avandia. Sen. Charles E. Grassley (R-Iowa) used the study's publication to push his proposal to reorganize the FDA's drug monitoring division. Meanwhile, Avandia users were no doubt staving off their own elevated blood pressure. Columnist Biographies, Past Columns and RSS Feeds Save & Share Article But there is good reason for the FDA to act cautiously. In an editorial after the review's publication, the Lancet, a respected British medical journal, pointed out that the two most significant studies considered did not produce many conclusions of statistical significance. The authors of the analysis admit that it suffers from significant weaknesses, among them that they did not have access to patients' medical histories. Further, the FDA has said that it has other data that contradict the analysis. A large trial is underway, the results of which will help to clarify the medication's dangers. In other words, the analysis is far from conclusive, and the FDA should not be in the business of regulating by suspicion. It always must balance potential dangers against potential usefulness of a drug. If anything, the episode makes the case for a bill that Sens. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) and Mike Enzi (R-Wyo.) recently shepherded through the Senate. The most potent criticism of the FDA's behavior in the Avandia case is that it hasn't moved fast enough to quantify the drug's dangers. The legislation would give the FDA clear authority to order post-approval studies if the regulator got a whiff of undocumented risks. The bill would also promote the pooling of public and private data on prescription drugs so that possible side effects can be discovered earlier and appropriate studies commissioned more rapidly. The House should embrace the Senate's approach. Sensor Continuously Monitors Glucose in Diabetics China Rejects FDA Warning on Toothpaste China Rejects U.S. Warning on Toothpaste FDA: Throw Away Toothpaste Made in China A Disservice to First Responders Related Topics & Web Content Top 35 Most Viewed Comments that include profanity or personal attacks or other inappropriate comments or material will be removed from the site. Additionally, entries that are unsigned or contain "signatures" by someone other than the actual author will be removed. Finally, we will take steps to block users who violate any of our posting standards, terms of use or privacy policies or any other policies governing this site. Please review the governing commentaries and discussions. You are fully responsible for the content that you post. &copy; 2007 The Washington Post Company The Washington Post Store The Washington Post Company: Information and Other Post Co. Websites 1996- The Washington Post Company User Agreement and Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-0&fd=R&url=http://www.hfxnews.ca/index.cfm%3Fsid%3D34195%26sc%3D89&cid=1116865706&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Halifax, The Daily News: News | 'Sleepsex' is often demoralizing and dangerous for bed partners Enter your search terms Monday, June 4, 2007 CHECK OUT OUR NEW COMMUNITY WEEKLY WEBSITES Dartmouth-Cole Harbour Weekly News Halifax West-Clayton Park Weekly News LETTERS TO THE EDITOR Send us a Letter Looking for a Job? Enter to Win a Trip for two to Montreal Z103.5 Hitmix 2007- Win 1 of 10 CD's Winner of The Ultimate Spring Home Indoor Makeover Contest Movie Contest Winners - Mr. Brooks Fire Call- Help Support NIE NIE - Newspapers in Education The Daily News and the Community Canada Winter Games - 2007 Canadian Census - 2006 Mount Saint Vincent University N.S. Sport Hall of Fame Nova Scotia Community College University of King's College Last updated at 7:15 AM on 02/06/07 'Sleepsex' is often demoralizing and dangerous for bed partners Doctors have come up with the first formal classification of "sleepsex," a wide range of abnormal nocturnal behaviours that emerge during deep sleep, such as sexual sleep-talking and intercourse with total amnesia. In a review article published yesterday in the journal , researchers from the Minnesota Regional Sleep Disorders Center and Stanford University School of Medicine say more and more reports are emerging of people engaging in unusual or "atypical" sexual behaviour while asleep. Eighty per cent of cases are male-dominated. Sometimes the sleepsex is a lot better than the waking sex: one woman commented she wished her boyfriend would incorporate some of the "forceful, albeit playful, biting" and dirty talk of their sleepsex into their conscious, daytime lovemaking. But in most cases, sleepsex ends not with couples lying in bed smoking cigarettes, but in physical injuries - bruises, cuts, fractures and sexual assault - as well as shame, guilt and embarrassment. One 27-year-old man broke two fingers when he tore off the restraints he used to try to avoid moving in bed and masturbating at night. Partners describe sexsomniacs as glassy-eyed and seeming "far away." One 38-year-old man sexually assaulted his spouse during sleep for 12 years. He once tried to choke her. "Losing control over yourself during sleep in a repeated way is very demoralizing and also creates problems in the relationship. Not just sexual problems but sleep disruptions," says Carlos Schenck, lead author of the sex and sleep paper. "On top of that, you're trying to have sex or even assault your bed partner or spouse sexually. It's very disconcerting and it can cause major problems in the relationship." What's more, Schenck acknowledges that adding sleepsex or "sexsomnia" to the official medical nomenclature risks giving rapists a convenient way to beat an assault charge. "But you would need strong clinical documentation, including support from the sleep lab." The Canadian physician who first described sexsomnia says the phenomenon is almost impossible to fake. "It happens while you're asleep. It's not under voluntary control," says Dr. Paul Federoff, forensic research director of the Institute of Mental Health Research at the University of Ottawa. A Toronto judge two years ago acquitted a 33-year-old landscaper of sexual assault after ruling the man was asleep at the time. The man met a woman one night at a party. She later fell asleep on his couch and woke to find him having sex with her. The man testified that he realized he was trying to have sex with her only after going into the bathroom and discovering he was wearing a condom. Federoff says that, according to the cases of sleepsex he's aware of, the activities are automatic and don't involve "such complex behaviours as finding a condom and putting it on." No one knows how prevalent sleepsex is because the surveys haven't been done, but Federoff believes it occurs more frequently than believed. Most cases of sleepsex are due to an underlying sleep disorder, says Schenck, a senior staff psychiatrist at the Minnesota sleep disorders centre. Schenck's team did a computerized literature search of peer-reviewed journal articles and scoured sleep medicine textbooks for descriptions of sexual activity during sleep. They found four cases of men with obstructive sleep apnea who initiated sex with their partners while they were sleeping. Not only were the men asleep, they were snoring. A nasal CPAP mask cured not just the apnea, but also the sleepsex. These aren't the "nocturnal emissions," or "wet dreams" described by sex researcher Alfred Kinsey more than 50 years ago. Sexsomnia behaviours range from masturbation, moaning, vocalizations, and fondling a partner to full sexual intercourse. Some people report sexual hallucinations and delusions after waking. Chronic insomnia can cause increased libido and "compulsive sexual behaviours." You're trying to have sex or even assault your bed partner or spouse sexually. It's very Dalhousie University discipline students accused of on-line cheating Girl found with porn suspect U.S. military judge dismisses charges against Canadian held at Guantanamo Bay A party 'Rae would enjoy' N.S. Liberals appealing $12,000 estimate for information on gas regulation Al-Qaida group claims to have killed U.S. soldiers captured in Iraq ambush Two men facing charges after stabbing in Lunenburg County RCMP release name of Nova Scotia man killed in weekend collision Cape Breton doctor suspended by medical college pending hearing Two arrested following theft of unique bamboo flutes in Bedford McNabs Island cleanup crew mystified by survival suit, flares and artillery pieces Two in hospital after car hits parked car Man wakes from coma after 19 years Shelling continues in Lebanon Surprise - you're getting married Identity theft is elder abuse: justice minster Doggie fundraisers help pets with cancer Hearn toasts class of 2007 IWK telethon earns record-breaking $4.8m Defence