http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-1&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/local/318405_metrics05.html&cid=1116954432&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Gates Foundation donates $105 million to UW for health center Skip ads and navigation Last updated June 4, 2007 12:25 a.m. PT Gates Foundation donates $105 million to UW for health center The Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation's desire to further Seattle's growing leadership in global health took another big step forward Monday with the philanthropy's donation of $105 million to the University of Washington -- the largest private gift ever to the UW -- to create the world's leading center of health program analysis and evaluation. "In medicine, we would never think to sell a drug that had not been completely shown to be safe and effective," said Dr. Julio Frenk, a former health minister for Mexico who is now a senior adviser to the Gates Foundation. "Yet we often think nothing of launching some large-scale social or health intervention without first doing the same kind of rigorous study to accurately identify the problem and most likely solutions," said Frenk, who played a critical role in creating the UW's new Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation. The new institute, also supported by $20 million from the UW and state government, will be directed by one of the leading experts in this frequently controversial field focused on judging success or failure in global health practices and policies, whether by foundations, governments, corporations or private organization. "My foray into this area was motivated by frustration with a simple question: What are the biggest health problems in the world, and where are people with these problems living?" said Dr. Christopher Murray, a widely known Harvard University economist who will direct the new UW health metrics institute. "The first thing I learned is that, in global health, everyone exaggerated the problem they were working on," Murray said. There was usually nothing sinister about this, he added; it was usually simply a good-faith attempt to muster more resources for a neglected problem. Though most assistance programs aimed at fighting disease or improving poor people's health are similarly well-intended, Murray said, many still are not based on an accurate assessment of either the problem or the most effective and available means for solving it. "The history of development projects, not just in health, is littered with enormous investments that very often don't yield anything," he said. Given today's new momentum for tackling many of the massive, chronic health problems in the developing world because of financial support from the likes of the Gates Foundation, other donors and governments, Murray said it's more critical than ever to ensure that these investments succeed. "Before Chris' work, the main way we did measurements in international health, or even domestic health, was to look at mortality rates," said Dr. Judy Wasserheit, vice chairwoman for the UW's new Department of Global Health (also financed in large part, by a Gates Foundation donation of $30 million). Murray, who also served in several leadership roles at the World Health Organization before moving his operation to Harvard, developed a metric of assessing the burden of disease according to a method now known as "disability-adjusted life years" or DALYs, developed with his WHO colleague, Alan Lopez. When you look at disease through the DALY lens, said Dr. King Holmes, a world-renowned expert on infectious diseases and chairman of the UW global health department, the problems out there can look quite a bit different. "The most common cause of death in Africa is communicable diseases," Holmes noted. But when you look at the non-fatal but disabling effect of all illnesses, including mental illnesses, he said, it quickly becomes clear that death rates are not always the best measure. "What we need to know is what makes people ill and what makes them well," Holmes said. The new institute headed by Murray will have faculty appointments in global health, he said, and will include studies looking at health policy in the U.S. as well as worldwide. "There are many reasons why children don't get vaccines in poor countries," added Dr. Pat Wahl, dean of the UW School of Public Health. Barriers to immunization can include economic, political, cultural and psychological factors, Wahl said, and Murray's expertise is in teasing out all of the reasons why health-improvement projects work or don't work. "This represents a tremendous step forward for the university and for all of the global health community," Wahl said. This is not the first time the Gates Foundation has invested in the need to improve the numbers in global health. At the 2005 World Health Assembly, Gates announced a grant of $50 million to create a Health Metrics Network aimed at assisting developing countries directly. "While academic institutions have a comparative advantage in teaching and research, they are not well-positioned to assist governments or to actually change the systems that deliver information on health," said Dr. Sally Stansfield, executive secretary of the Geneva-based Health Metrics Network. Stansfield, who previously served as director of global health initiatives for the Gates Foundation, said her organization intends to collaborate closely with the new UW institute to make sure the advances achieved in Seattle are rapidly and effectively deployed at the country and community level. The impetus for creating the new UW institute appears to have come when Dr. Tachi Yamada, director of global health programs at the Gates Foundation, met with Frenk in Mexico. Frenk, who had worked with Murray at the WHO, convinced Yamada of the need for a new, independent entity that can monitor and evaluate global health projects. "Julio was pretty excited about the possibilities," said Yamada, who went on to discuss the idea with Murray. "We really need that kind of analysis to guide the decisions and decide which directions we should take in the future." Murray, since leaving the WHO, has been highly critical of the U.N. agency's ability to evaluate and monitor the effectiveness of health programs worldwide. Some at the WHO, based in Geneva, Switzerland, privately grumble that the new UW institute represents a challenge to the WHO that could undermine its authority for setting priorities in international health. "I don't see it that way at all," Yamada said. The intention, he said, is for the UW institute to work in close collaboration with the WHO -- to provide assistance and full access to the data just as an independent consultant might work with a business. There is also the concern that the new institute, having been created and funded by another rising world health organization, the Gates Foundation, might go easy on the criticism when analyzing the performance of the Seattle philanthropy's own global health efforts. "Well, that's why we're locating the institute at a world-class university with an independent advisory board," Murray said. "Universities are social institutions designed to provide for doing the kind of work that is sometimes inconvenient to powerful people." The Harvard economist and his colleagues did recently give only passing marks to the Gates Foundation's largest single health project, the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization. Murray and his colleagues determined that immunization rates in countries that started with very low rates of coverage were making progress, whereas countries starting with more than 65 percent of children covered were not doing very well. "That has caused a little bit of discussion, which is the point," he said. "These kind of things need to have a demonstrable effect. Good intentions are not good enough." P-I reporter Tom Paulson can be reached at 206-448-8318 or What do you think? Add P-I Local headlines to Jogging Elvises and more Keep it simple with a high-tech kitc