http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-2&fd=R&url=http://www.canada.com/reginaleaderpost/news/story.html%3Fid%3D8db7d434-c74d-47db-ab8f-5e3c404138f1&cid=1116367587&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Survivors, families mark win over cancer canada.com, Newspapers, TV, Radio See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter canada.com where perspectives connect in the Leader Post Jobs in Regina working.com 10 year archive in FPinfomart See today's Digital Edition Subscribe to email newsletter Find a job at working.com Find a car at driving.ca Find an apartment at renting.ca Find real estate at Homes Find great stuff at shopping Selling? Place an ad Meet a match at Connecting Headlines marked with a are exclusive to subscribers. Update credit card information Send us a news tip Setting a world record Mosaic was a chance for thousands to discover world traditions and an opportunity... Going after identity thieves Surfing for porn in Afghanistan 9/11 border security has little impact on trade; costs more Canada can't meet Kyoto targets: Harper Cottages, condos will be hot buys of the future: report Survivors, families mark win over cancer Published:Â Monday, June 04, 2007 The Relay for Life Survivor Rally is a celebration of life and a poignant reminder of how many lives have been touched by cancer, said Carla Redler. "My husband is a 25-year cancer survivor. So when Relay for Life came to Regina in 2002, and because we had journeyed with cancer since 1982, I just embraced this event. It was all about the celebration of life and coming together,'' said Redler, who helped organize the survivor pep rally. "We have always said cancer is a family disease. Even though it was my husband who was diagnosed with cancer our whole family went through the journey with cancer and we all survived it.'' The Royal Saskatchewan Museum held the Relay for Life Survivor Rally on Sunday. Email to a friend On Sunday more than 300 survivors and their families took part in the third-annual survivor rally which was held this year at the Royal Saskatchewan Museum. "When I heard about this event I told my husband, 'I need to do this for you honey.' I sat beside his bed every time Tony had cancer, and he had cancer four times between 1982 and 1995, and every time I would sit there and feel so helpless and I couldn't do anything,'' Redler said. "I said 'I need to do this for you. I need to celebrate life. I need to put on a party for you.' And then I got to meet the other 175 survivors that joined that first year and I said 'Hey, this is way bigger than you. Now we need to reach every survivor we know and invite them.''' The rally is a chance for survivors, who will be walking the victory lap during the June 15 Relay for Life fundraising walk to meet each other and share their stories. "We don't recruit survivors. We simply invite them to the party and if they want to celebrate with us on June 15 we are going to give them a day that they will not forget,'' Redler said. "We are going to have an amazing event. We are going to have more teams than we have every had in the past. We are preparing for 500 survivors to come out and join us,'' she said, adding 86 teams are already registered for the relay. Jennie and Benny Yee will be among the survivors. Jennie was diagnosed with stage 4 lymphoma which had spread to her bone marrow in 2000 and her husband was diagnosed with cancer in 2004. "When I learned I had cancer I cried for three days and on the fourth day I prayed to God to take away my worries. I said I'm not going to worry about it if you want me to go, because I could be hit by a car crossing the street and die,'' Jennie said. Instead of focusing on dying of cancer the Regina couple said they acknowledged they had cancer and focused on celebrate each day as survivors which has helped others within the Chinese community break down that wall of silence around the disease. Â© The Leader-Post (Regina) 2007 Scandal Sheet: Brad Pitt Brad Pitt was spotted in