http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-3&fd=R&url=http://english.people.com.cn/200706/04/eng20070604_380504.html&cid=1116898077&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg People's Daily Online -- China says U.S. self-contradictory detaining toothpastes from China China at a glance China in brief 2004 CPC & state organs Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping UPDATED: 09:32, June 04, 2007 China says U.S. self-contradictory detaining toothpastes from China China said Saturday it was closely watching the U.S. detainment of toothpastes from China and urged the U.S. side to clarify the facts and solve the problem in a prompt and proper way. An official with the General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine said the U.S. importers have submitted the formula of China's toothpaste exports to the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) before shipment and the content level of diethylene glycol (DEG) were indicated on the packaging. "All the toothpastes were registered with the FDA and approved to be distributed in the , so they contradicted themselves by warning consumers to avoid using China-made toothpastes and detaining shipments from China," said the official. On June 1, the FDA warned consumers to avoid using tubes of toothpaste labeled as made in China, and issued an import alert to prevent toothpaste containing the poisonous chemical DEG from entering the United States. According to the FDA's website, FDA inspectors identified and detained one shipment of toothpaste at the U.S. border, containing about 3 percent DEG by weight. They found and tested toothpaste products from China located at a distribution center and a retail store. The highest level found was between 3-4 percent by weight. In 2000, Chinese experts claimed after carrying out tests on 1,965 people that toothpaste containing less than 15.6 percent of DEG was harmless for humans. So far there have been no reports of people being poisoned by toothpaste containing DEG. In addition, the U.S. side allows the use of DEG in food addictive according to its laws and the FDA said on its website "it is not aware of any U.S. reports of poisonings from toothpaste containing DEG". The safety of Chinese food and drug products has been in the news lately. China has blamed Panamanian traders for falsifying documents on a Chinese chemical product that resulted in the deaths of dozens of Panamanian people who ingested tainted cough syrup and confirmed the alleged toxic toothpaste imported from China to Panama met safety standards. "Over the past two years, the acceptance rate of China's food exports to the United States has hovered around 99 percent, slightly higher than that of U.S. food exports to China," said said Li Yuanping, an official in charge of food import and export safety. Comment on the story Gov't probes 'tainted toothpaste' case China promises to dig out truth on alleged tainted toothpaste Copyright by People's Daily Online, all rights reserved
http://www.dogflu.ca/06042007/15/get_married_to_cure_depression&cid Get Married to Cure Depression | DogFlu.ca Ontario Animal Shelter Contact Information Health Information for Human Beings Human Conditions and Diseases Get Married to Cure Depression Researchers are reporting that if somebody is depressed, they should get married as this has been proven to lift the mood of people dealing with the mental health condition Feeling a little down in the dumps? Why not get Married! New research suggests that getting married can lift your mood, even though married life may not be as uplifting. "Based on previous research, we hypothesized that people who are depressed would have worse marital quality and would therefore experience fewer benefits from marriage but that is not what we found," researcher Adrianne Frech said in a statement. The team pulled data for their study which is published in the Journal of Health and Social Behaviour, from the National Survey of Families and Households. They were able to learn that people who were depressed to a certain degree had relief of their depression upon getting married. Results from the study also showed that married people who are depressed, tended to report less marital happiness and more marital conflict but overall, their moods were more upbeat. Click Here to Join the Discussion! at 2007-06-04 19:59 | Copyright Â© 2006 DogFlu.Ca All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-6&fd=R&url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/69199.html&cid=1116865706&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Abnormal sexual behavior often results in sleep disorders Abnormal sexual behavior often results in sleep disorders Mon, 04 Jun 2007 16:36:00GMT Create your own RSS People who suffer from certain types of sleep disorders are likely to have a risk of exhibiting inappropriate sexual behaviors during their sleep, according to a new study appearing in the journal Sleep. This phenomenon called "sexsomnia" or "sleepsex" is occurring with increasing frequency among patients prompting experts to define it along with some parameters. Sleepsex involves either masturbating or making advances even while in deep sleep, the study said. Sleepsex is often mentioned in the same set of disorders which include sleepwalking, sleep talking and night terrors. A collective term used for the above conditions is parasomnia. Lead researcher Dr. Carlos H. Schenck of the Minnesota Regional Sleep Disorders Center said that some inappropriate sexual behaviors occur during wakefulness as well. "We wanted to call attention to how virtually all known categories of sleep disorders carry a risk for inappropriate sexual behaviors," said Schenck. He gave an example called Kleine-Levin syndrome in which affected patients could sleep for 16 to 18 hours at a stretch, but when awake could indulge in "hypersexual" behavior. "Basically, an alarm rings in their nervous system when it shouldn't ring, and they have this partial awakening. It's a twilight state," he said, adding that such people might harm themselves because they have no control over their behavior. The study said that clonazepam (Klonopin) could take care of such problems in 90 percent of the cases. Copyright &copy; 2007 Respective Author Email this article (Click Here) Share this article on &raquo; - Toddlers who snore likely to be hyperactive children: study | 04 Jul 2005 - Sleep disorders linked to school work | 22 Jan 2007 - Sleepless children, sleepless adults | 01 Mar 2007 - Doctors dismiss sleep complaints of elderly | 04 Jan 2007 - Study favors use of actigraphy | 02 Apr 2007 Liver cancer drug seen as effective Bathing your baby daily might harm its skin Initiatives can lure more to walk Spanish doctors convert man's right hand into his left China orders unfit schoolchildren to start dancing The views expressed in the articles are not necessarily those of earthtimes.org and we accept no responsibility for the views or opinions expressed in the articles either direct or indirect. , All Rights Reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-5&fd=R&url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation/story/134858.html&cid=1116948981&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg www.kansascity.com | 06/03/2007 | &lsquo;Heeling&rsquo; may leave kids hurting '[/mi/registration/request/user_run_mode]', regex=>'1', case=>{ '.' => '[/registration/production/registration_css.comp]' } --> Sign in to your Classified Account Sign in to Classifieds The Star's Front Page The Kansas City Store Movie Passes: "NANCY DREW" Movie Passes: 'OCEANS 13" Trip to Breckenridge, Colorado Crested Butte, Colorado Trip Posted on Sun, Jun. 03, 2007 &lsquo;Heeling&rsquo; may leave kids hurting A new study blames a rash of injuries among children on the popular wheeled sneakers. Sneakers with retractable wheels in the soles &#8212; Heelys is the most popular brand &#8212; are all the rage among kids around the world. Doctors, however, warn about the risk of injury. CHICAGO | Wheeled sneakers let kids zip down sidewalks, but doctors say the trendy shoes also can send children rolling into emergency rooms on stretchers. The craze is called &#8220;heeling,&#8221; named after Heelys, the most popular brand of wheeled sneakers. The shoes are sold in 70 countries and are so hot that their Texas-based maker, Heelys Inc., recently landed atop &#8217;s annual list of fastest-growing companies. However, doctors have reported treating broken wrists, arms and ankles; dislocated elbows and even cracked skulls in children who were injured while wearing roller shoes. In a 10-week period last summer, 67 children were treated at Temple Street Children&#8217;s University Hospital in Dublin, Ireland, for injuries from Heelys or strap-on wheels called Street Gliders. The data appear in in the June issue of the journal From September 2005 through December 2006, one death and at least 64 roller-shoe injuries were reported to the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission, an agency spokesman said last week. The American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons this week will issue new safety advice that recommends helmets, wrist protectors and knee and elbow pads for kids who wear wheeled shoes. &#8220;As these shoes are sold in department stores, parents buying them may develop a false sense of security &#8212; that they are like any other shoe,&#8221; said James Beaty, the academy&#8217;s president and a pediatric orthopedic surgeon in Memphis, Tenn. Heelys and their knockoffs look like gym shoes, but with wheel sockets in each heel. They can be used for walking, but the wheels pop out when users shift their weight to their heels. Balancing on the wheels can be tricky, especially for novices. In the Irish study, most injuries were in new users and occurred when the kids fell backward while trying to transfer their body weight. Leon Benson of Evanston Northwestern Healthcare in Evanston, Ill., recalled treating a 9-year-old girl who&#8217;d had her Heelys for just a week when she fell and broke both wrists. Noah Woelfel of Davidsonville, Md., wasn&#8217;t a novice but still tripped and fell, breaking several fingers and wrist bones in his right hand last year. &#8220;All it took was a tiny piece of gravel in the driveway that went up in the wheel and stopped him cold,&#8221; said the 9-year-old boy&#8217;s mother, Nancy Woelfel. &#8220;He required surgery and pins, and he was six weeks without using his hand, right at the beginning of school.&#8221; Nancy Woelfel threw the removable wheels away. In April, Heelys Inc. said that a study it commissioned showed that the wheeled shoes had a safer injury rate than skateboarding, inline skating and swimming. The shoes are sold with safety information, which includes a recommendation to wear protective gear. About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company Terms of Use & Privacy Statement
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-2&fd=R&url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/N04447748.htm&cid=1116946098&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Reuters AlertNet - Bayer,Onyx liver cancer drug extends life 3 months Mon Jun 4 18:12:15 2007 Central African Republic troubles Georgia, Abkhazia, S. Ossetia Intense tropical cyclone Jaya Severe cyclonic storm Akash South Sudan fragile peace Super cyclonic storm Gonu Child danger poll 2006 Diamonds and resource wars Democratic Republic of Congo St Vincent & Grenadines United States of America Take the AlertNet Quiz Bayer,Onyx liver cancer drug extends life 3 months 04 Jun 2007 12:12:54 GMT 04 Jun 2007 12:12:54 GMT ## for search indexer, do not remove--> (Repeats to add subscribers) (New throughout, updates with share price, background, analyst rating change) CHICAGO, June 4 (Reuters) - A drug already used to treat kidney cancer became the first medicine to extend the life of patients with advanced liver cancer in a clinical trial, adding about three months to survival compared to a placebo, according to a study released on Monday. The trial found the biotechnology drug Nexavar, by German drugmaker Bayer AG and its U.S. partner Onyx Pharmaceuticals , extended survival by 10.7 months, compared with 7.9 months for those on a placebo -- a 44 percent survival benefit -- sending Onyx shares about 10 percent higher in pre-market trading. "Of about 100 trials in liver cancer in 30 years, all have been negative. There is an unmet need," said Joseph Llovet, director of liver cancer research at Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York, who led the trial. Liver cancer kills 622,000 people globally each year and is treated with a mix of surgery, radiation and chemotherapy. But there are no effective treatments when these aggressive options fail, and Bayer and Onyx hope to be first to fill that treatment gap. Because of the survival advantage, the 600-person study was halted early so that all patients taking part could receive the drug, taken in pill form. The result led Bear Stearns to raise its rating on Onyx shares to "outperform" from "peer perform," according to theflyonthewall.com. The liver cancer data on Nexavar, among a new wave of treatments targeting cell receptors to block cancer growth, were presented at the American Society of Clinical Oncology's annual meeting in Chicago, where tens of thousands of cancer experts are gathering. Although relatively uncommon in the United States, liver cancer is the third biggest cause of cancer deaths worldwide, largely due to the high incidence of hepatitis abroad that can lead to liver cancer, according to the World Health Organization. Nexavar, known generically as sorafenib, is being tested against several types of cancer. Bayer plans to submit its full applications seeking approval to sell the drug for liver cancer with U.S. and European regulators this summer, according to a spokesman. The data presented at this meeting will likely lead to increased off-label use of the drug for liver cancer by doctors even before it is approved for that indication. The companies however cannot promote the medicine for that use until it gains official regulatory approval. Liver cancer is primarily caused by exposure to the hepatitis B and C viruses, which can occur through sharing dirty needles, unprotected sex, in childbirth and from blood transfusions. Alcohol and smoking are also risk factors. Once the virus is acquired, it can take several decades to develop into cancer. The disease is spreading at varying rates throughout the world because of the timing of exposure of different populations. For example, in Japan, a public campaign to vaccinate for tuberculosis in the middle of the last century inadvertently spread the virus via unsanitary injection needles, Mount Sinai's Llovet said. Rates in Japan are still high but have leveled off, while in the United States the virus began spreading quickly in the 1970s with increasing use of illicit drugs with hypodermic needles, he said. In the United States, liver cancer kills about 17,000 people annually, but the rate is growing faster than in many other countries. Onyx shares jumped about 10 percent in pre-market electronic trading to $34 from their $30.88 Nasdaq close on Friday. Bayer shares were little changed in Germany. (Additional reporting by Bill Berkrot in New York) news is provided by Judge's ruling may halt all Guantanamo trials FEATURE-Germany in climate change dilemma ahead of G8 Insurgent video shows IDs of missing U.S. soldiers FACTBOX-Security developments in Iraq, June 4 Top US general says too early to judge Iraq plan InterAction Statement on President's Renewed AIDS Plan Source: InterAction - USA American Red Cross Promotes Prevention and Control of Tuberculosis Along U.S. - Mexican Border Source: American Red Cross - USA Leader of AJWS Grantee Wins Prestigious Human Rights Award Source: AJWS - USA Catholic Relief Services commends President's call to double PEPFAR funding Source: CRS - USA World Vision U.S. Welcomes President's Global AIDS Funding Proposal Source: WV - USA For our full disclaimer and copyright information please visit http://www.alertnet.org
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-4&fd=R&url=http://www.dentalplans.com/articles/18868/&cid=1116949820&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Depressed People Have More to Gain From Getting Married > Depressed People Have More Depressed People Have More to Gain From Getting Married Updated: 6/4/2007 12:09:00 PM (HealthNewsDigest.com) - Marriage provides greater psychological benefits to depressed people versus people who were not depressed before they walked down the aisle, a new study reveals. This remains true even though marriage quality is poorer for depressed individuals. Sociologists Adrienne Frech and Kristi Williams, Ph.D., from Ohio State University in Columbus co-wrote the study. It appears in the June issue of the American Sociological Association's Journal of Health and Social Behavior. â€œBased on previous research, we hypothesized that people who are depressed would have worse marital quality and would therefore experience fewer benefits from marriage,â€ Frech said. â€œBut that is not what we found.â€ The researchers speculated that marriage may provide a level of companionship that depressed singles typically lack. Frechâ€™s team used data from the National Survey of Families and Households. The study included 3,066 never-married, divorced or widowed individuals under age 55. To identify depressed individuals, researchers used a 12-item test for depression. Respondents were considered depressed if they scored 23 or more points on the test. After a follow-up period of five years, researchers identified people who got married, the quality of their marriages and how their psychological well-being changed. The study excluded participants who married but ended up divorcing before the five-year follow-up. Researchers found that all participants who married within the five-year period scored an average of about 3.5 points lower on the depression test than those who remained single. Of all the depressed participants, those who got married scored an average 7.5 points lower on the mood scale than the people who remained single. The nondepressed experienced a smaller change in their psychological well-being if they got married.Results from the study confirmed that depressed people report less marital happiness and more marital conflict. Nevertheless, being married enhanced their mood. Previous studies suggest that depressed people benefit from stable social support more than the nondepressed. Robin Simon, Ph.D., an associate professor of sociology from Florida State University in Tallahassee, agrees that this is likely. â€œThe studyâ€™s findings make perfect sense to me. One symptom of depression is loneliness and lack of companionship. I am not surprised that marriage would supply a psychological boost for the previously depressed,â€ she said. &copy; Copyright by HealthNewsDigest.com Enter your ZIP code to compare the savings and benefits offered by the discount dental plans in your area. Take the first step toward a healthier smile and start saving today! Find a ZIP code This Fathers Day, Focus on the Three Tip... The First At-Home Fertility Screening fo... MU Researchers Find Mechanisms that May ... AMA - Medicare Cuts Will Hurt Seniors Women Up to Age 30 at Risk for Bone Loss... Depressed People Have More to Gain From ... VA To Establish Nursing Academy Advances in Treatment of Epilepsy and Re... What is Causing the Dramatic Decline in ... What is the Terminator seed Proposed for... Second SPORT Study Results: Clear Advant... Better Understanding of Tumor Cell Activ... Math that Powers Spam Filters Used to Un... MIT Reports Key Pathway in Synaptic Plas... Visualizing the Molecules that Cause Inf... Training the People Who Advance the Scie... Mannequins that Bleed: Take a Real-life ... Caller ID in the Wild: African Elephants... Good Eating Habits Check Them At The Do... More Than a Fish Story: Bringing Steelhe... Search Plans & Dentists Tell a Friend About Us Return to Home Page Dental Insurance vs Dental Plans Planes D