http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-4&fd=R&url=http://www.courierpostonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070603/NEWS01/706030393/1006&cid=1116367587&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg New faces join relay for cancer CourierPostOnline - South Jersey's Web Site Give a gift subscription Submit a news tip Spot News Kids Korner Letters to the editor Weddings, Engagements & Anniversaries New faces join relay for cancer The cancer survivors' lap officially opens the Relay for Life at Washington Township High School on Friday. The race raises millions of dollars nationwide for the American Cancer Society. Cancer survivor Rob Becker is filmed by Michael Pietrobon at Saturday's race at Haddon Township High School. Becker is featured in an American Cancer Society national recruitment video. Cancer survivor Rita Ralston of Washington Township holds her granddaughter, Isabelle Nutt, 3, during the survivor's lap Friday at Washington Township High School. Sunday, June 3, 2007 When Rob Becker first attended the American Cancer Society's Relay for Life, just a few months after his doctors declared him cancer-free, he was reluctant to walk with other survivors. "Some of these people have gone through so much," the 43-year-old Cinnaminson High School history teacher said. "I didn't feel I survived anything. I had a couple of surgeries and some treatment." It took the Cherry Hill resident five years to take his place among the survivors at the yearly overnight walk-a-thon. "I did it to celebrate being a cancer survivor for five years," Becker said. "That was five years ago and since then, I've become more and more involved. I started to understand what it means to be a cancer survivor. It means having the willpower to fight the disease and not let the disease take over your life." Now the once-reluctant survivor is taking his message of hope to relay participants nationwide. On Saturday, camera crews followed Becker, who will be featured in a Relay For Life recruitment video, as he walked with about 50 other area survivors around the Haddon Township High School track. The overnight event is a fundraiser where teams of people take turns walking or running laps. The video, which will be distributed to Relay participants and be available on the Web, is being shot at three locations -- each representing one portion of the relay's new slogan, "Celebrate, Remember, Fight Back." Becker's survival story will constitute the celebrate portion of the video. The remember portion of the video will focus on someone who lost his battle with cancer and the fight back portion will focus on a current patient. Those portions will be shot in North Carolina and Massachusetts. "They picked him because he has become increasingly involved as a survivor," said American Cancer Society national spokeswoman Karen Becker, Rob's wife. "He volunteers year-round for the American Cancer Society." Rob Becker was among the roughly 500 participants in this year's event, one of 11 relays in South Jersey and 4,800 nationwide. Last year, the Haddon Township relay raised $46,000 for the American Cancer Society. This year, officials expect to raise $407 million nationwide, Karen Becker said. "We raise that 10 bucks at a time," she added. Relay participants, many of whom camp overnight, raise money all year in preparation for the event. Some sell baked goods and refreshments to raise more. The roughly 20 members of Team Mimi were among them. They signed up for the first time last year to honor Mary "Mimi" Williams of Pennsauken, who had just died of lung cancer. "We wanted to do something to keep her memory alive," said Christine Margenthal of Haddonfield, Mimi's daughter. "We want her to know the fight she went through wasn't in vain." Mimi never got to meet her first grandchild, born four months after she lost her battle with cancer. She'll also never see the child Margenthal is expecting, her first. "They'll know her," Margenthal said. "We keep her memory alive. That's why we're here." Reach Lavinia DeCastro at (856) 486-2652 or send a letter to the editor This article does not have any comments associated with it Find a used car to buy Find a used Car: Find a New Car Send feedback about CourierPostOnline.com Copyright ©2007 Courier-Post. All rights reserved. Users of this site agree to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights (Terms updated March 2007) .Build 0: 751 ms (Misc) .Build 9: 0 ms (Content)
