 post-operative reports from two patients who had brain surgery, and then used them to accompany dummy claims. Canella is still on lam, for fraud of over $142,000; he and the other participants, who are from Manhattan, Mount Vernon, and Staten Island, will face between 30 and 90 years for mail and health care fraud. Advertisement: Gothamist Continues Below! Are you aware of our Comments: (you may use HTML tags for style, but you can only add links if you've signed in) Your preview will show up here. Start typing! *Tags allowed: a href, b, i, br/, p, strong, em, ul, ol, li, blockquote, pre . All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-1&fd=R&url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/wireStory%3Fid%3D3238592&cid=1116866873&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg ABC News: Is Killer Storm Still Taking a Toll? Is Killer Storm Still Taking a Toll? Almost 2 Years Later, Debate Rages Over Whether Katrina Is Still Killing New Orleans coroner Dr. Frank Minyard is seen in this May 29, 2007 file picture in New Orleans. Nearly two years have passed since Hurricane Katrina left behind death and destruction, but many in the medical community here say the storm is still killing. "There is no doubt in my mind that Katrina is still killing our residents," Minyard said. (AP Photo/Bill Haber) By MARY FOSTER Associated Press Writer NEW ORLEANS Jun 2, 2007 (AP) The bodies are no longer being dragged from houses and buildings toppled by Hurricane Katrina, but nearly two years later many in the medical community think the storm is still killing. Storm survivors are dying from the effects of both psychological and physical stress, from the dust and mold still in dwellings to financial problems to fear of crime, health experts and officials say. "There is no doubt in my mind that Katrina is still killing our residents," Orleans Parish coroner Dr. Frank Minyard said this week. "People with pre-existing conditions that are made worse by the stress of living here after the storm. Old people who are just giving up. People who are killing themselves because they feel they can't go on," Minyard said. Some say an in-depth federal analysis is needed, despite a new state report that found no significant increase in deaths in the New Orleans area from January 2006 through June 2006. The state Department of Health and Hospitals is still compiling figures for the last six months of 2006. Dr. Raoult Ratard, the state epidemiologist, said "the only slight increase" in deaths was in the first three months of 2006 in Orleans Parish. But New Orleans medical officials say that jump, from 11.3 per 1,000 deaths to 14.3 per 1,000, a leap of more than 25 percent was anything but slight. Moreover, the report doesn't take into account evacuees who died while away from the city and were returned for burial. "Our death rate was already high, that's huge," said Dr. Kevin Stephens Sr., director of the New Orleans Health Department. Some New Orleans doctors questioned the accuracy of the population figures used to determine the death rate, saying they might have been too high. DHH secretary Dr. Fred Cerise said he was comfortable with the population data, which he said came from the Census Bureau and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. The city was abandoned after Katrina struck Aug. 29, 2005, and many people did not begin returning until mid-2006. Is Killer Storm Still Taking a Toll? Comment on This Story WHAT OTHERS ARE SAYING Add to the facts. Tell us what you know. Currently there is no ballot question for this story. Do you have an idea for something to ask? Send it in here! Discuss this topic with the ABC News Community Chat About Health and Fitness Issues Citizen Journalists: Click Here To Ask The Newsmakers Questions Check out the video discussion going on now E-mails & News Alerts Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights External links are provided for reference purposes. ABC News is not responsible for the content of external internet sites. Copyright &copy; 2007 ABCNews Internet Ventures
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-2&fd=R&url=http://www.ajc.com/health/content/health/stories/2007/06/04/0605lvskateinjuries.html&cid=1116948981&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg On a roll, kids at play risk great deal of pain | ajc.com News Q & A Atlanta / South Fulton Casinos, Golf, Ski, & More On a roll, kids at play risk great deal of pain School's out, and children are taking to the streets for summer fun. But retailers and physicians are warning them to walk, not roll. Wheeled footwear has been tied to knee injuries; arm, hand and shoulder fractures; broken limbs; and at least one death. Doctors says Heelys and knockoffs shouldn't be worn without wrist guards, knee pads, helmets and other protective gear. With the press of a button or push of their heels, kids can now whiz down sidewalks and across floors thanks to trendy roller shoes, a popular brand of which are called Heelys. But zipping around on a wheel or two has landed kids in the emergency room. Between September 2005 and December 2006, at least 64 injuries and one death were reported to the U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission because of the wheeled shoes; millions have been sold since their arrival around 2000. Injuries have included arm, hand and shoulder fractures, broken toes, feet and legs, concussions and knee injuries. "When you look at the severity of the injuries, it should give a parent concern," says agency spokesman Scott Wolfson. "If you're going to pick up the wheeled sneaker product then your next purchase should be a helmet." Injuries to children and the pedestrians they often run into have prompted local retailers such as Party City to ban rolling around in the shoes. At Simon Mall properties, including Lenox Square and Phipps Plaza, they are not banned, but use of the roller feature is prohibited. This week, the American Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons issued new safety guidelines, including helmets, wrist protectors, and elbow and knee pads for kids wearing the roller shoes. Heelys Inc., the maker of Heelys, issued a press release on its Web site saying that a study commissioned by the company showed that using the wheeled footwear is "significantly safer than bicycling, skateboarding, basketball, soccer and even tennis." However, Heelys Inc. says that the shoes should be used with protective gear. The company offers seminars for kids at stores and parks and videos on its Web site. Children's Healthcare of Atlanta orthopaedic surgeon Michael Bush gives some advice to prevent more children from rolling into the ER: Do the wheeled shoes pose a risk because of design or user-error? "It's a combination of the two. It's like wearing roller blades, so you can have a sudden fast fall; it happens fast. People don't realize that you can get hurt from sudden falls because you don't have time to compensate. (It's the difference between a unicycle and a bicycle). The kids have them on, and they wheel down the mall, they are being distracted, and they fall." What types of injuries are most common? "Since your weight is placed behind you, you get a lot of upper extremity fractures because you tend to reach out and try to protect yourself. I treated a kid with a thigh bone fracture that required surgery. When I went home that afternoon, my daughter said that her mother was going to buy her some Heely's. I said 'No way!' " What would make them safer? "The only thing that would really help would be safety equipment such as wrist guards and helmets." Two girls killed in fight at graduation party Lizard Kills 8-Year-Old in Indonesia Magic: Donovan 'conflicted,' contract talks continue Patrick confronts Wheldon after on-track incident Girls shot to death at party identified Search staff-written and other selected articles. from 1985 to present from 1868 - 1929 Find the right people for the job: The voice of Georgia's Hispanic community since 1979 El vocero de la comunidad hispana de Georgia desde 1979
