http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-0&fd=R&url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2007-06/04/content_886065.htm&cid=1116898077&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Safety watchdog rejects US FDA's toothpaste warning Safety watchdog rejects US FDA's toothpaste warning By Zhu Zhe (China Daily) The country's top quality watchdog this weekend strongly disagreed with a warning by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) over the safety of Chinese toothpaste, saying it was "unscientific, irresponsible and contradictory". In response to an FDA notice saying toothpaste made in China may contain a poisonous chemical, the General Administration of Quality Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine (AQSIQ) said in a statement that it is safe to consume the chemical in question in small quantities. "Our research shows that toothpaste containing up to 15.6 percent diethylene glycol, the chemical that the US side is concerned about, is safe, even after prolonged use," the statement said. The US started checking Chinese toothpaste imports on May 23 as media reports that the products may contain diethylene glycol, a solvent sometimes used as a substitute for glycerin, a sweetener used in drugs. After finding Chinese toothpaste containing 3-4 percent diethylene glycol, the FDA on Friday issued a warning about toothpaste made in China. However, experts from the Chinese Health Ministry said that diethylene glycol is a "low-level" poison that does not accumulate in the body, and said there is no evidence that it can cause cancer or deformities. The AQSIQ also said that a list of the ingredients in the toothpaste exported to the US had been offered to the FDA. The list included diethylene glycol. Also, the toothpaste's labeling had already been registered with the FDA, meaning it could be sold in the US. "Therefore, the FDA warning is unscientific, irresponsible and contradictory," the AQSIQ said. "We've lodged a representation to the FDA and asked it to clarify the facts in a scientific manner as soon as possible." Joseph Famulare, an official with the FDA's center for drug evaluation and research, who was in Beijing attending a workshop this weekend, told China Daily that the US laws ban diethylene glycol as an ingredient in toothpaste. He said recent safety scandals highlighted the importance of being aware of all the ingredients and intermediates in products. To improve the quality of management and the regulatory framework for drug manufacturing, he said the FDA and Peking University had jointly launched a new graduate program on pharmaceutical engineering management. (China Daily 06/04/2007 page3) Six dead, five injured in SW China road collision Chinese Vice Premier Huang Ju dies US, China to set up defense hot line soon Defense budget true and authentic UN chief praises China's role in Darfur FMs of China, S.Korea, Japan meeting in Jeju China: US FDA toothpaste warning unscientific Strong quake in SW China kills 3, injures 290 Chinese Vice Premier Huang Ju dies China plans military hotline with US Most Commented/Read Stories in 48 Hours
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-6&fd=R&url=http://www.dailypressandargus.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070603/LIFESTYLE/706030318/1024/CUSTOMERSERVICE02&cid=1116867696&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Press & Argus - www.livingstondaily.com - Livingston, MI Welcome to Press & Argus Livingston, MI Make us your Homepage Monday, June 4, 2007 Carolina DeLuca: Protect kids from the sun June has finally arrived with its hot sun — so very welcome after the prolonged cold of winter. Now we can enjoy the outdoors: playing, swimming, having picnics. While you are planning summer activities, take a minute to plan for protection against the sun. The Skin Cancer Foundation tells us that skin cancer rates in the United States are increasing at epidemic levels. There is good news, however. Parents can teach their children early sun protection techniques that will help prevent skin cancer later in life. The following recommendations are offered as methods of protection for different age groups. The skin of babies is extremely sensitive and can burn easily. Babies under 6 months old should simply not be in the sun, period. Keep them out of the sun and shaded at all times. For babies over 6 months, follow these tips: ¸ Take walks early in the morning or late afternoon. Use a stroller with a sun-protective cover. Dress babies in loose-fitting clothes. Choose light colors. You can buy clothing made with a UPF of 30 or higher. Check the Internet for pertinent sites. One such site, recommended by the Skin Cancer Foundation, is . A portion of proceeds go to the Skin Cancer Foundation. Protect the babies face, neck, and ears with a hat. If they start wearing a hat in early months the child will get used to it. To protect your baby's eyes, since they can't wear sunglasses, look for the shade between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m. Apply a broad-spectrum, SPF 15+ sunscreen to areas left uncovered such as baby's hands. In the car, you will need to use a UV-blocking window film. Active toddlers require a little more thought to keep them protected. You will need to leave instructions for caregivers, also. Arrange for your child to play in the shade. A broad-spectrum SPF 15+ sunscreen should be applied every morning, 20 minutes before leaving the house. Keep sunscreen in the bathroom where children brush their teeth, and they will begin to associate applying it with their daily routine. Sunscreens should have both UVA and UVB screens. UVA screens keep the sun from burning the skin, but does not protect the lower layers under the skin. Lotions with UVB screens will protect from UVB rays, which are chiefly responsible for burns. Two tablespoons of sunscreen must be applied every two hours and more often if your child is swimming or sweating. Perspiration washes off the Children should wear sun protective clothing, including shirts, hats and sunglasses. During prolonged exposures, they should wear wide-brimmed hats, long-sleeved shirts and pants. Most of the protection methods used for toddlers and young children should be applied to elementary school children. Teach your children the shadow rule: When outside, if your shadow is shorter than you are, then the sun is high in the sky and the UV rays are intense. Dress children appropriately. Tightly woven fabric that you can't see through easily offers the best sun protection. Oversized T-shirts are OK. Avoid skimpy clothes and sleeveless T-shirts that leave the most vulnerable areas, like the shoulders, exposed. The ears, shoulders, and backs of the neck are most often burned while children are playing. A wide-brimmed hat is a useful protective clothing item that should be worn during recess. Eyes can also be damaged by exposure to the sun. They can be protected by sunglasses with UV (ultra violet) coating. Teach your child to look for the shaded areas in which to play. Carolina DeLuca is former program director of the Child Protection Council, a program of the Women's Resource Center. This article does not have any comments associated with it Originally published June 3, 2007 E-mail this to a friend Copyright &copy;2007 Livingston Daily Press & Argus Users of this site agree to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights (Terms updated March 2007) .Build 0: 375 ms (Misc)
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-6&fd=R&url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/features_julieshealthclub/2007/06/no_wheelies_on_.html&cid=1116948981&ei=iIBkRoWhMY-oqgPRnJWcBg Chicago Tribune | Julie's Health Club A forum on personal, family and environmental health issues. &laquo; Men overwhelmed by grocery shopping Originally posted: June 4, 2007 A new childhood threat: roller shoes I was awed the first time I saw a kid in Heelys, the rolling shoes with the stealth wheels embedded in the heels. The young child had been walking normally when he suddenly shot across the lobby of the YMCA. They struck me as a disaster waiting to happen, even though the company says you shouldn't "heel" faster than you can walk. But if that's the case, what's the point of using them? So far, they've been banned by some shopping malls, schools and amusement parks and were considered one of the 10 worst toys for kids last year by the World Against Toys Causing Harm (W.A.T.C.H.) in Pediatrics shows that the shoes are particularly dangerous for beginners and girls. Last summer, the orthopedic department of a Dublin hospital saw 67 childrenâ€”56 girls and 11 boys-- for injuries suffered while using "roller shoes" known by the brand names Heelys and Street Gliders. Fractured and dislocated arms, wrists and shoulders were the most common injuries in the children, who ranged in age from 6.2 to 14.9 years. More than half of the injuries occurred in beginners and none of the children had been using protective gear when injured. The authors weren't sure why more girls were injured and speculated that perhaps more girls wear Heelys. Most said they would continue "heeling" or "street gliding" after their injuries healed. One of the problems with the shoes is that they're a cross between sneakers and recreational equipment, said Steven Krug, head of the Division of Emergency Medicine at Childrenâ€™s Memorial Hospital. "Most people buy them as footware and donâ€™t assume the necessary precautions," said Krug. "Theyâ€™re not quite roller skates and not a bicycle, but the same sort of problems can occur. Iâ€™ve taken care of kids who see a nice little ramp and engage in Heely mode. Maybe you make it, maybe you donâ€™t." It's also hard to get kids to wear protective gear when they're walking and suddenly decide to glide twenty feet. Most aren't going to strap on a helmet and wrist pads every time they want to spontaneously roll. The Heelys company says the product is safer than biking, skateboarding, basketball, soccer and even tennis. But the other sports have more children participating. And is Heeling even a sport? Regardless, if you have a beginning "heeler" or you want to try them yourself to catch the bus or break twenty minutes in a five-kilometer race, here are a few roller shoe tips from Heelys: Heelys recommends protective gear when the wheels are in the shoes and coincedentally sells a helmet and protective pads for ($19.99) Always stagger your feet with your strong foot in front â€“ putting them side by side will result in your feet sliding out from under you. When walking with the wheels in, do not lean back on your heels and make sure to walk with your toes touching the ground first. Be extra cautious when heeling on uneven surface â€“ debris and crevices can cause sudden stops and uncontrolled movements. When you feel like you are losing balance, step out of heeling by putting your toes down and lean forward. Good gravy, are we going to get rid of all risk of injury to kids and watch them continue to balloon into fat gobs of teenage goo because we won't let them do anything? I'm 42 and had my share of childhood bumps and bruises. I'm determined to have my kids grow up and not be overly protected from the owies of life. Let's see who handles life better when they are in their 30's; my kids who understand that life hurts sometimes or the ones who have never experienced anything negative before in their lives. Posted by: Kevin Raz | Ju