 my way to the back of the store. (Seems like everything you really want is always in the back of the store, right?) It really is 100% safe. I've never run into anyone. The #1 question I get asked when I'm heeling: "wow, where did you find a pair in your size?" They're available on eBay or at Mervyn's and Big 5 sports. Remember that there's a significant learning curve involved here, and you'll build up ankle muscles you never knew you had. But after you're practiced up, it's an excellent way to get around. For all those naysayers: with something that's currently this popular with the youth, and has the potential to make the everyday commute easier, there's a good possiblity that it won't die out like the hoola-hoop. I expect that in another decade these heely-proficient youth will still use the shoes to get around. I recommend going out and trying it for yourself to see what all the fuss is about before you blindly try to get the shoes blacklisted. Posted by: Lorin Thwaits | Jun 4, 2007 11:37:09 AM Jeez enough with overprotecting kids. Everything can be dangerous; the tub, eating, walking out your front door on a blustery day, walking on an icy sidewalk. I look back at some of the dumb things I did as a kid, playing on the roof, jumping bikes off of ramps or into the river. Skeeched in the winter behind buses on icy roads. I've lived and have stories to tell. No helmet or knee pads. Had my brusies and bumps, broke my nose a few times. That's part of being a kid. Parents, educate your kids on consequences and then they're on their own. Cross your fingers and things will turn out ok. The elementary school by my home actually has a sign on the playground that says, "No Running". Can you believe it? The school got tired of being sued by parents when their kids got boo-boos. Enough already. Posted by: BillS | Jun 4, 2007 11:43:19 AM "She doesn't race. She doesn't do stunts. She's not allowed to." Yeah, keep telling yourself that. Posted by: Jack Armstrong | Jun 4, 2007 